<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JUL 93 / Langbaurgh left in options limbo: The review of local
government structure itself faces radical revision after fierce controversy.
FT reporters examine the issues
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ANY CONFUSION over precisely which is the Local Government Commission's
preferred option for the Cleveland borough of Langbaurgh is, it says, in the
minds of inattentive journalists influenced by hostile publicity.
In May the commission announced its preferred Cleveland option was four new
unitary authorities, including Langbaurgh, based on existing borough council
boundaries.
One non-preferred option was to scrap Langbaurgh, splitting its territory
between Middlesbrough and a new Yorkshire unitary authority.
Then in June the commission announced its preferred option for North
Yorkshire, based on the historic Ridings. 'The North Riding would cover the
area of the present districts of Hambleton, Richmondshire, Ryedale,
Scarborough and (possibly) that part of the district of Langbaurgh which was
formerly in Yorkshire,' it said.
This, critics say, conflicts with its preferred Cleveland option. Not so,
says the commission. 'You have preferred option A, which is with Langbaurgh,
and preferred option B without it,' it said.
The commission added that while it was obliged to state a preferred option,
'it's still hedged around with a degree of vagueness because further
consultation could lead the commission to change its mind'.
What Langbaurgh's 143,000 residents think is far from clear. Only 582
returned a coupon in the council's free newspaper, delivered to all 59,000
homes, requesting their views. Of the 582, 35.7 per cent backed the
commission's preferred Cleveland option.
</TEXT>
