<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JUL 93 / Business gives VAT rules cool response
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE FIRST six months of the European single-market rules on value added tax
have yielded no benefits for the UK companies affected, a survey by
accountants Price Waterhouse shows.
Respondents asked to compare the possible benefits - such as the savings in
time to carry goods across the European Community - with drawbacks - such as
the additional requirements to report trade data - said they had not gained.
The abolition of customs checks on January 1 meant companies had to record
their own VAT information and compile their own trading records.
Smaller exporters and importers are required to file quarterly trade figures
to Customs while larger traders must make monthly returns.
Customs has calculated that the changeover would cost British business
Pounds 100m in the first year but then lead to net annual savings of Pounds
135m.
The survey showed that 68 per cent of companies questioned were financially
worse off than before. The biggest single difficulty was the completion of
the trade statistics.
One middle-ranking multinational had found compiling the trade data so
complex that it had failed to make any returns.
The second main area of complaint was the changes companies had to make to
their computer systems. One company spent Pounds 500,000 on its computers.
Mr Mike Arnold, VAT partner at Price Waterhouse, said transport companies
did not appear to be passing on the benefits of faster transport times
either in their schedules or in the prices they were quoting.
There were also difficulties in dealing with some other member states,
notably France, Italy and Spain. Some countries insisted on foreign
companies registering locally for VAT while UK companies had encountered
problems in obtaining the VAT registration numbers of customers in these
countries.
Forty six per cent of the UK companies interviewed said they were not
looking forward to the prospect of a second round of VAT changes, intended
to simplify the system and planned for 1997.
Only 30 per cent were in favour of the next round of changes.
Price Waterhouse's respondents ranged from 'smallish' public companies to
big multinationals, to which it provided VAT advice in the approach to the
single market.
</TEXT>
