<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JUL 93 / Spring warns against N Ireland select committee
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR DICK SPRING, the Irish foreign minister, yesterday warned that the UK
government should not set up a select committee on Northern Ireland.
His comments came amid continuing speculation that the understanding forged
last week between the government and the Ulster Unionist party would lead to
the creation of a cross-party committee of MPs. The party's nine MPs backed
Mr John Major, the prime minister, in the critical Commons votes on the
social chapter, having made clear that they expected changes to restore
'accountable democracy' to Northern Ireland.
Mr Spring said the Irish government had to take notice of the assurances
from Mr Major and Sir Patrick Mayhew, the Northern Ireland secretary, that
the British government had not reached a deal with the Ulster Unionist
party. He underlined, however, the need to ensure that events at Westminster
over the past few days 'should not cause any further difficulties for
Anglo-Irish relations'.
Mr Spring said: 'At this stage it would be unwise to start addressing this
problem on a bit-by-bit basis. The only way is by bringing about an overall
agreement acceptable to both communities.' He added: 'This will involve
compromise, hard decisions and hard choices. And I don't think anything
should be done in the meantime, like, for example, setting up a select
committee.'
The terms of the understanding between the UUP and the government are
clouded. Both say there has been no formal agreement, but the UUP sees
longer-term benefits from its backing for the government.
The Rev Ian Paisley, Democratic Unionist Party leader, last night accused Mr
Spring of an unwarranted interference in the affairs of a sovereign state.
He said: 'If John Major has any integrity at all he must demand that Dick
Spring and the Irish government desist from this intolerable interference.'
</TEXT>
