<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JUL 93 / St Columbus's salutary lesson for the banks: The growth of
the credit unions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT and JOHN GAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AS BANKS digest last week's opinion poll showing a steady fall in the number
of customers satisfied with their services, they could take a salutary look
at the St Columbus parish in Bradford.
Eighteen months ago, after the main bank in the area closed its branch, the
parish set up a credit union. The union has now taken over the old branch
and is running a service that its 180 members think meets many of the roles
of the bank.
Mr Joseph Yewdall, a voluntary worker at the union and a chairman of the
National Federation of Credit Unions, said: 'There's a lot of people here
who have no access to banks. I think we're showing that there can be an
alternative.'
The St Columbus story is more common than it used to be. After decades of
being regarded as a poor man's social fund, the credit union movement is
growing fast, doubling in number from 203 in 1989 to an estimated 405 last
month.
The UK form of credit union involves up to 5,000 people who have a 'common
bond', such as working for the same employer, forming a savings fund.
Members are usually allowed to borrow up to three times their savings, up to
Pounds 5,000.
Credit unions are not allowed to 'leverage' their funds by lending more than
deposits. In return, and on the assumption that the 'common bond' will make
members wary of defaulting, they do not have to hold capital.
Mr Michael Parkinson, chief executive of the Association of British Credit
Unions, said assets and membership had risen by 40 per cent in the past
year, and the 190 credit unions in his association controlled about Pounds
30m of savings.
The movement is still in its infancy compared with the US and Ireland, where
23 per cent of the population are members. Mr Derek Lee, the registrar of
friendly societies and the unions' regulator, describes it as 'tiny'.
Yet Mr Al Charbonneau, chief executive of the World Council of Credit Unions
in Wisconsin, is impressed by the growth rate.
Nevertheless, he warns that it will be 'many years yet' before Britain's
credit unions are able to offer the wide range of financial services
provided by unions in the US, Canada and Australia - including the issuing
of credit cards.
One reason for the growth lies in the increasing reluctance of banks and
building societies to open their doors to poorer customers - leaving the
unions as almost the only source of cheap loans and savings accounts for
many.
While credit companies such as Provident Financial, which collect weekly,
charge annual percentage rates of interest on loans running into three
figures, credit unions are legally allowed to charge only 1 per cent a month
 -12.7 per cent APR.
At St Columbus union workers said most residents could not get a bank
account. One said: 'Never mind the money, to get a bank account you need a
10-year passport or driving licence - and people around here just haven't
got that.'
The credit union, by contrast, has a relatively open-door policy. Any member
of the local community can join without needing to provide extensive
documents.
Members of the credit union who prove to be reliable are allowed to take
larger loans. Those who save receive an annual dividend, usually about 5 per
cent, calculated by dividing the annual surplus made by the union.
Like most credit unions, St Columbus also offers a bill paying service and,
in conjunction with the local TSB bank, household and life insurance
policies. It is required to invest funds securely under the Credit Unions
Act 1979.
A second reason for growth is the shift in the composition and clientele of
the new unions. Although the movement has been best known for its
'community' based unions, its fastest expansion is in the workplace.
According to Abcu 60 per cent of the movement's assets are held in employee
unions. These range from local government unions to those in the police
force and taxi services. This month British Airways has become the first
private-sector company to establish a union for its 48,000 employees.
Expansion has forced more professionalism on the credit unions, with some of
the larger ones employing full-time staff. But it has also led to growing
demands for new financial powers along the lines of the US unions.
Mr Graham Tomlin, the BA engineering manager who set up the union, wants it
to be able to offer mortgages, cheque books and credit cards. 'I don't see
why we couldn't do that. The demand is definitely there,' he said.
Yet such ambitions may cause some prudential worries about the movement. The
act envisaged unions retaining enough profits to hold reserves equal to 10
per cent of assets, but the figure stands at 7.18 per cent.
In addition, Mr Lee said he was 'disappointed' that the industry had not
responded to pressure to ensure that depositors would not lose all their
savings if a union collapsed.
Officials from the Registry of Friendly Societies are meeting credit union
managers to consider proposals for legal reform. The movement would like
legislative reform to be put to parliament soon.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
