<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JUL 93 / Sheehy defends proposals for police shake-up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
VERY FEW police officers are likely to have their careers 'abruptly
terminated' if fixed-term contracts are introduced by the government, Sir
Patrick Sheehy, chairman of the committee recommending the change, says
today.
Proposals to introduce fixed-term contracts are the most controversial
element of the Sheehy report. It recommends that all officers should be
employed on initial 10-year contracts, subsequently renewable every five
years.
Sir Patrick, writing in today's Financial Times, defends his committee's
radical proposals for changes in police pay and conditions. He accuses the
Police Federation, which represents the majority of officers, of having been
long on emotion and short on factual content in its response.
The Sheehy committee's proposals - which include performance related pay and
abolition of three ranks - have drawn opposition from all the police staff
associations.
Pressure on the government to tread carefully mounted yesterday when Mr Paul
Condon, Metropolitan Police commissioner, said he might be unable to
continue in his post if some of the reforms went through.
Mr Condon, 45, who was handpicked by Mr Kenneth Clarke when home secretary
to modernise Britain's biggest police force, said in an interview in the
Observer newspaper that he would 'find it very difficult to be a well-paid
commissioner, presiding over a demoralised, badly-paid Metropolitan Police'.
While supporting some Sheehy recommendations, such as those for a flatter
management structure, Mr Condon said the inquiry had not understood the
motivation and nature of policing at street level.
The suggestion that the Sheehy committee has produced unrealistic
recommendations because none of its members had experience of policing has
been a consistent police service claim in the three weeks since the report
was published.
Sir Patrick, chairman of BAT Industries, says in his article that the
committee 'fully recognised that our lack of professional experience of
working with the police service made it vital that we should learn about the
police at first hand'. During 55 visits to 24 forces, he says, committee
members found that constables felt badly managed and chief officers lacked
the tools to manage them.
Sir Patrick describes the claim that fixed-term appointments would be
inconsistent with the concept of the police service as a vocation as a
'curious argument'. The only reasons for refusing to renew a contract would
be medical unfitness, gross misconduct, manifest incompetence, or structural
grounds.
Blueprint for better policing, Page 18
Observer, Page 19
</TEXT>
