<HEADLINE>
FT  26 JUL 93 / ERM pressure builds as threat to franc grows: Bundesbank
urged to consider problems of other EMS members
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN and DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESSURE on the European exchange rate mechanism looks set to build again
this week ahead of Thursday's meeting of the Bundesbank central council.
Mr Pedro Solbes, Spanish finance minister, urged the Bundesbank to take the
problems of other European Monetary System members into account. 'The EMS
cannot live in a situation of permanent crisis,' he told the Financial
Times.
Large-scale intervention by the Bundesbank and Bank of France on Thursday
and Friday of last week did no more than hold the French franc at just over
1 centime above its lower intervention point in the ERM. In active trading
in Tokyo early today, the franc edged down from an opening level marginally
below FFr3.40 against the D-Mark.
Foreign exchange market operators now say that only a significant cut of
perhaps 1 percentage point in German interest rates will save the franc.
However, it is doubtful whether the Bundesbank could agree to such an easing
of credit conditions in the face of continued inflationary pressures in
Germany.
Although the Bank of France and Bundesbank have a formidable reputation for
defending the franc and giving speculators a 'bloody nose', developments in
financial markets late last week were inauspicious for the French currency:
Market assessments of the scale of a Bundesbank rate cut required to
alleviate the crisis rose steadily on Friday, from around half a percentage
point in the morning to a full point by the end of currency trading in
Europe;
Equities in Paris advanced on Friday, showing that investors there expect
the government to cave in to speculators and cut interest rates in the same
way the British government did after last September's departure of sterling
from the ERM;
Conservative bond market investors and pension fund managers were reported
to be moving funds out of the French into the German bond markets in the
expectation of a currency gain from a franc devaluation or suspension of the
ERM;
New York hedge fund managers confirmed that they had so far played hardly
any role in the latest round of speculation against the franc. But some made
clear that they were preparing to act this week unless there were clear
signs of the Bundesbank lowering interest rates.
Market analysts also say that the French banking system is in a less strong
position than before to support the French government's efforts to shore up
the franc through higher rates.
French banks co-operated with the government by not passing higher interest
rates to corporate and individual borrowers in the crises of last September
and early this year.
Banks are less able to take such a strain after suffering losses this year.
Moreover, the French government is in a worse position to 'twist arms' among
the state-owned banks because it is preparing them for privatisation and
cannot risk destroying their profitability.
The French prime minister, Mr Edouard Balladur, whose government has
repeatedly vowed to defend the franc's status in the ERM, is due in London
today with President Francois Mitterrand. That message is likely to be
repeated in their talks with the prime minister, Mr John Major.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
