<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / Hawks &amp; Handsaws: Wolf at the door
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL THOMPSON-NOEL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
I HAD another chess lesson yesterday in the company of two friends: Queen
Elizabeth II, head of the House of Windsor, and John Major, prime minister
of Britain. We are preparing ourselves for the world chess championship
tussle in September between Britain's Nigel Short and the title-holder,
Russia's Gary Kasparov. Our teacher is Nigel himself.
The Queen is the star pupil, for she demonstrates mid-game finesse, deep
strategic skill, and end-game brutality. Nigel has warmed to her greatly;
his affection is reciprocated. John Major is the dunce: unable to master
tactics, utterly free of guile, and a ditherer to boot. Nigel treats him
kindly.
With the country teetering on the brink of a bottomless chasm, you might
think it strange that the Queen and prime minister found time to indulge
themselves in a chess lesson. I was surprised they turned up. But they
always keep their appointments.
The Queen chimed and shone. She is convinced that the danger in which her
family found itself earlier this summer is receding. The monarchy is safe.
It has had to trim its sails, but there will be a king (or queen) of England
long after she has gone. The prime minister, however, is not yet aware of
the danger he is in. He is still a cheery chappie - like a dinosaur happily
munching while the asteroid that will obliterate it settles into its
approach run.
Yesterday, we were supposed to be studying Nigel's game against Ljubojevic
(Reykjavik, 1987), in which he used the Yugoslav Attack. But our hearts were
not in it. There was far more chat than chess. The Queen was worried in case
Nigel was being hounded by the media in the run-up to his title match.
She said: 'It is imperative that one is not distracted from one's mission in
life by the tittle-tattle of gossips, or by pensees creuses. The newspapers
are appalling. But book-writers are worse. There has been such a flood of
books about oneself and one's family that one was in danger of submerging.
'For example, there was a book recently by the dreadful Anthony Holden in
which this provincial little man - he really is quite short, you know, and
was born in the north of England - had the gall to estimate the cost of the
monarchy to the British taxpayer in 1992 as exceeding Pounds 75m, or Pounds
192,000 per day - 'more', claimed this common little person, 'than 13 times
the average national wage, before tax, per year.'
'What an impertinence. With whom did this gobe-mouches check his facts? One
could have pointed him in the right direction had he consulted oneself. But
of course he did not telephone one. How could he possibly dare? Lupo
affamato mangia pan muffato, Nigel - a famished wolf eats mouldy bread.
Whatever you do, avoid journalists and book-writers. They will stab you in
the back.'
'Actually,' said Nigel, 'it's really brill at present. No one is hounding
me. They've forgotten I exist. People have convinced themselves that
Kasparov the Barbarian is going to tear me into such small and bloody pieces
that they're avoiding me like the plague.'
'I wish I could say the same,' said the prime minister soulfully. 'It is a
considerable surprise to me how consumed the media are with negative
matters. Because the Maastricht treaty has encountered a few administrative
difficulties in the House of Commons, the political journalists - a
singularly ill-informed group, if I may venture to say so - are whipping up
hysteria.
'But you only have to peruse the inside pages of the newspapers to
acknowledge that many excellent developments are happening in Britain. We
have the strongest economy in Europe. The number of abortions in England and
Wales fell in 1991 for the first time since 1983. A considerable enlargement
of the M25 orbital motorway has been announced.
'The long-range weather forecast is particularly excellent. Our cricketers
are reasserting themselves. Crime is falling. Arrests are rising. The number
of operations conducted in our hospitals is increasing all the time. We have
much to be proud of. Our astronomers at Greenwich have even spotted a new
asteroid. I believe it is a large one. It is emitting steam and flames. When
I get home tonight I plan to observe it, through my binoculars.'
Just then, the lesson ended.
</TEXT>
