<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / As They Say in Europe: 'Football and television inebriate
rapidly'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES MORGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AS WE ride the great Euro-Community not-very-merry-go-round, one passenger
after another falls ill. Not as unwell as some of those on the outside, but
worse than they have been for 40-odd years. Britain, Germany and Italy have
all appeared sickly. Now eyes are turning to France.
The French franc has been transformed in a matter of days from a potential
currency anchor to speculators' favourite. That was linked, on the face of
it, to some unsurprisingly gloomy forecasts about immediate prospects for
the economy.
However, the team of analysts employed by this column detected two entirely
different factors undermining the republic. The first was the extraordinary
wound inflicted by the great football scandal which has undermined the
presidency, the system of justice and made everyone look unusually stupid.
New readers begin here: the story opened with the allegation last month that
the European champions, Olympique Marseille, had become champions of France
by bribing members of the Valenciennes team to throw a crucial match.
A common enough tale of footballing folk, you might think, but the boss of
OM is the renowned socialist millionaire Bernard Tapie, while the procurator
for Valenciennes, Eric de Montgolfier, turned out to be a man who relished
the opportunities for cutting a dash hitherto denied him by run-of-the-mill
villainy.
He appeared frequently on TV to discuss the case and his role in it. As a
result, he was called in by the minister of justice and told to shut up.
Meanwhile, the same minister was suing Bernard Tapie, who had compared the
state's investigative techniques unfavourably with those of the Gestapo.
De Montgolfier promised to behave better and called a press conference to
protest his innocence. And, in an exclusive interview with Liberation, he
said he regretted only one remark: 'I am distracting the pack.' By this he
had meant that he kept the media at bay while the investigation proceeded.
The remark had been inspired, said de Montgolfier, by an event at an al
fresco press conference. A municipal registrar standing on a roof had taken
a photo of the procurator which showed his bald head surrounded by a hirsute
press mob.
Liberation wrote: 'Football and television inebriate rapidly. Mixed with a
certain wilfulness in the administration of justice, we are in an infernal
cocktail.' The presumption of innocence, said some, had been forgotten.
President Mitterrand, on the other hand, while demanding prudence in the
conduct of the case, had praised the 'energy' and 'intelligence' of his
friend Tapie,' . . . as if these qualities in themselves were guarantees of
honesty and moral rigour,' wrote Ouest-France.
The second cause of the republic's present discontent is to be found in the
crisis at the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development which ended
in Jacques Attali's departure a week ago.
This event destroyed a substantial market for French suppliers who, under
the benign rule of Attali, had had no need to worry about such details as
competitive bidding. The affair added to the mood of self-doubt. France-Soir
summarised it characteristically: 'Attali, Jacques. Graduate of the
Polytechnique, the School of Mines, Sciences Po, National School of
Administration (ENA), doctor in economic science. The finest collection of
degrees in the republic. A head, a brain, a machine for thinking . . .
Jacques Attali. Delirium. Megalomania.'
French megalomania is beginning to upset the Germans - always an unwise
move. Klaus Engelen of Handelsblatt was sufficiently upset to ask: 'Why
can't the French let others run an international financial institution once
in a while?' The Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development and
the International Monetary Fund are led by Frenchmen and Paris says that it
has the right to appoint Attali's successor.
Engelen's view, expressed with his customary tact, is that once the French
control anything they exploit it ruthlessly. 'The IMF was turned into a
self-service shop for French and US interests. The French get the top jobs,
the Americans all the power and the Germans and Japanese provide the money.'
But Engelen is mistaken. The French are not like that, at least not
according to an opinion poll which led Ouest-France to comment: 'In today's
France, which moans about its fate while reading its balance sheets, beliefs
are not what they are said to be. Skilled, educated, cared for, the French
today want only tranquility. Their happiness lies above all in good health,
then work followed by love, justice and friendship. Money is their last but
one concern.'
Football, television and megalomania come nowhere, apparently.
James Morgan is economics correspondent of the BBC World Service.
</TEXT>
<XX>
