<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / Arts: A conductor who fell in love with Europe - Andrew
Clark profiles Donald Runnicles, a British star who has forged his career
abroad
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW CLARK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHEN Donald Runnicles lifts his baton to conduct Tannhauser at the Bayreuth
Festival on Monday, it will not be without a sense of irony. He is only the
third British musician to be invited to conduct at Bayreuth in the
festival's 117-year history - but his success owes little to his British
origins.
Runnicles has made his career almost entirely outside Britain, and seems in
no hurry to come back. In spite of his apparent neglect by our orchestras
and opera companies, the 39-year-old Scot from Edinburgh says he does not
feel like a prophet without honour in his own land. He has received
invitations from ENO, Covent Garden and Scottish Opera - but they clashed
with other commitments.
The truth is that Britain has missed the boat with one of the most gifted
conductors of the younger generation. When Runnicles did have time, he was
snapped up by continental and American companies who recognised dynamic
musicianship when they saw it. He made his Met debut in 1988 with Lulu. He
was appointed music director of the San Francisco Opera in 1991. His
Bayreuth debut came last year. Next month he conducts Don Giovanni in
Munich, followed by The Ring and Salome at the Vienna State Opera. Upcoming
are engagements in Berlin, Chicago and Israel, lined up by Columbia Artists
Management, the New York agency which manages his career.
Runnicles' outstanding assets are his technical control, the personal
conviction he brings to every piece of music he conducts, and his intimate
understanding of opera, based on practical experience. Energy, passion,
theatrical sweep - these are qualities often cited in Runnicles
performances. After a Mahler Third Symphony last season in Freiburg, where
he has just ended a four-year contract as Generalmusikdirektor, Runnicles
was dubbed a 'Mahler Ekstatiker' - pacing the music coherently while living
for the moment.
Unlike some better-known but less talented contemporaries trumpeted by the
recording industry, Runnicles had the good fortune to learn his craft out of
the limelight. He studied at Edinburgh University and the London Opera
Centre, but instead of waiting for one of the handful of junior conducting
posts in Britain to become vacant, he opted to work his way up the German
opera house system. His first job was as ballet pianist in Mannheim. Within
a year he was on the opera staff, and by the time he left Mannheim nine
years later in 1987, he had conducted 40 operas.
It was a tough apprenticeship, but it taught him the nuts and bolts of
conducting - how to start and stop an orchestra, how to modify a chord by
gesticulation, how to pull off a successful performance without rehearsal.
'The advantage of starting off in Germany is the regularity of performance,
night after night. It's going into a pit feeling fresh, feeling ill, feeling
prepared, feeling slightly terrified, going in knowing there's a new Leonore
and meeting her just before the performance. I'm not suggesting a similar
situation is not possible in Britain, but in Germany it is an everyday
occurence.
'In a house like Mannheim, you are confronted with a huge repertoire -
tonight it's Italian, tomorrow German, then French. The younger you are when
you start learning these works, the easier they are to absorb. It can sound
a bit like a sausage machine, but there are so many challenges - just to
find out that you can always do it. The best way to learn conducting is to
conduct, but the set-up of opera in Britain means that unless you are a
staff conductor with one of the main companies, you don't get enough chances
to make conducting second nature.'
Although he maintains a strong interest in British music, from Vaughan
Williams to David Matthews, Runnicles makes no claims to be 'particularly
patriotic', and says his home at the edge of the Black Forest will continue
to serve as his European base. In spite of his growing list of guest
engagements, he is at heart a company man, and refers to his San Francisco
job as a long-term commitment. But he is already being tipped as a future
music director in one or other of the big German cities.
What is clear is that more frequent British appearances - never mind a
London debut - are unlikely in the foreseeable future. He pays tribute to
Anthony Whitworth-Jones, Glyndebourne's general administrator, for 'keeping
at it' until the right opening appeared - a unanimously praised Don Giovanni
at the 1991 festival. And it will be at Glyndebourne that Runnicles next
conducts opera in Britain - Queen of Spades in 1995. There are also the
makings of a link with the Edinburgh Festival: following his Scottish
Chamber Orchestra concert there last year, he will open the 1994 festival
with Mahler's Eighth Symphony.
Son of the choirmaster and organist at the episcopal church in Morningside,
Runnicles says his church background has always been an important influence.
'That's where I learned organ and piano. It's sometimes hard for me to find
common ground between this background and conducting a work such as Salome,
so sensuous and seductive that it's almost corrupting - I almost feel as if
it's a sin to be enjoying it] This was never the music we heard at home. It
was me with my radio when I was growing up, listening to Bayreuth broadcasts
while the family were downstairs - I wanted to hear it. Ever since, church
music has been something terribly sobering and purifying, and at the end of
a day I still listen to it. I need that, because this operatic world which I
love is just one inflated ego.'
The 1993 Bayreuth Festival opens tomorrow with a new production of Tristan
und Isolde. Donald Runnicles conducts Tannhauser on July 26, August 1, 7,
14, 18 and 23.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
