<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / Arts: How many orchestras do we need? - Sir Alan Peacock
adds his voice to the Arts Council cash debate
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIR ALAN PEACOCK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Arts Council has had a difficult time over the recent decision to fund
only two orchestras in London. Following a long tradition of assuming
infallibility in cultural judgments, musical pundits have ritually
castigated the Council for having the courage of its convictions. But it has
taken nearly 25 years for the Arts Council to endorse the findings of the
closely-reasoned Report of the Orchestral Resources Enquiry published in
1970.
Let me declare an interest. I was the chairman of that enquiry, which
included among its musician members such luminaries as Malcolm Arnold, Myers
Foggin and Thomas Russell. Lord Goodman, the then chairman of the Arts
Council, disregarded the advice of his music committee and offered the
committee the choice of revising its conclusions or having them denounced on
publication. The committee refused to budge. A charter for sensible funding,
not only of London but of all government-assisted orchestras, was torn to
shreds.
In the interim, our ideas have regained currency. The more thoughtful
internationally-known conductors and players have recognised that squaring
the interests of those who perform music with those who have to pay the
piper is a much more complex matter than would appear from the emotional
outbursts of musical interest groups. I am proud of that report but my views
on funding the arts have changed considerably since those days.
Such views cannot be divorced from one's value judgments about the 'good
society'. I would like as many people as possible to have the opportunity to
enjoy good music and to be so taken with it that they are willing to pay for
it. Only the integration of arts education with our general education will
achieve such an objective. There is a dilemma in the case of music because
many serious composers of today are not primarily interested in winning over
the public but in maximising their reputation with each other. There is
nothing inherently wrong in their doing so - at their own expense.
I calculate that no orchestra in the UK can afford to offer living composers
more than 10 per cent of its programme time. Still, I support the funding of
new and unfamiliar musical experiments. However, the general aim to be
achieved - I suspect never completely - will be to adopt funding methods
which win the public round to voluntary support so that state funding
becomes unnecessary. The emphasis in funding should shift towards supporting
music societies and educational institutions, and even individuals through
voucher systems targeted to particular groups.
It is a far cry from this description of the ideal to the realities of
direct funding of major symphony orchestras (along with all large arts
companies) which have acquired all the advantages of incumbency. If we have
to live with this method In the meantime, then some of its worst features
should be eradicated.
The most important one is that it encourages the belief among the big
players that they have a right to direct funding in perpetuity. This is
surely wrong. The interest of the tax-paying public is in specific art
forms, music being a major one, and the 'demand mix' will change as public
tastes develop. That being so, the system of direct subsidy must be flexible
between different art forms and between those wishing to provide the
services required within each art form. There should be more open
competition for funding. Arts companies should hold 'franchises' for a
number of years, after which the franchise holders would have their
performance measured against that of possible new entrants.
The Arts Council proposals for funding London's orchestras is therefore a
step in the right direction, and I hope that it will pave the way for the
more flexible funding arrangements that I have proposed.
First, the concentration of funding to achieve artistic excellence makes
sense. Second, it would be wrong to 'Balkanise' artistic funding and give
the London so-called 'national' orchestras, opera and ballet companies
direct access to the Department of Heritage. This is merely a device for
special treatment which conflicts with the present policy of increasing
access to arts events nationally. There is no reason why the top slice of
arts funding should be allocated to metropolitan institutions, and every
reason why the Arts Council should decide on the 'opportunity cost' of
funding them, alongside the alternative uses of funds.
Third, those who have mocked the setting up of a committee under Sir Leonard
Hoffman which will recommend who will join the LSO as the second funded
orchestra lay themselves open to the charge that they believe that any
recommendation should be supplied only by those who represent the producer
interest. I agree that a necessary condition for being chosen must be clear
evidence of artistic excellence, but this in itself is not a sufficient
condition. Evidence of good management and a firm commitment to winning
audiences for adventurous programmes must also be provided.
The Arts Council is an easy target. Those who are denied funding protest
about those who get it, and those who get it protest that what they get is
not enough. Being a member is the easiest way of losing friends and
alienating people. The Bard says somewhere that 'rich gifts wax poor when
givers prove unkind'. Whatever decision the Arts Council eventually takes
about the second orchestra, reasonable people may disagree with it. The
trouble is that the voice of reason may be difficult to detect among those
who trade in cultural polemics. When it comes to spreading light rather than
heat about the funding of the arts, the musical public is at present
particularly poorly served by influential metropolitan critics.
Sir Alan Peacock was Chairman of the Scottish Arts Council (1986-92). The
themes in this article are expanded in his forthcoming book, Paying the
Piper, to be published in September by Edinburgh University Press.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
