<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / Arts: Kirov's tarnished treasure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLEMENT CRISP
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GREATEST treasure in the Kirov Ballet's repertory is The Sleeping
Beauty. This ultimate exposition of the grandeur and noble aspirations of
academic dancing was made at the Mariinsky Theatre for the troupe whose
direct descendants we see today. Across war and revolution and social
change, through siege and the dissolution of a political system, the
miracles of Tchaikovsky's score and Petipa's choreography have been
preserved in a dance style as serene in proportion, as civilised in
humanity, as the great city which gave them birth. To sit in the Mariinsky
Theatre and watch Beauty, is to sense something of the moral implications
('Dance is a moral question,' said Balanchine, product of this theatre's -
and of Beauty's - traditions) as well as the physical harmonies the ballet
celebrates.
The Kirov has toured Beauty since its first venture to the West with the
Covent Garden season of 1961. Then Beauty looked sublime, in ensemble as in
the performances of such glorious artists as Kolpakova, Sizova, Zubkovskaya,
Sokolov, Solovyov. Whatever the vicissitudes of the company's history
thereafter, I have felt that Beauty was the touchstone of its qualities, the
vital point of reference for the troupe's well-being. Touring imposes
constraints upon effects and, maybe, casting. But in Thursday's performance
that brought the piece into the Coliseum repertory, I noted erosions of
manner, accommodations of effect, which minimised the piece, and the
company's golden reputation.
The staging looked cramped - which it did not at Covent Garden - and
somewhat cursory. Was it necessary to reduce the Hunting scene - whose
autumnal grace the Kirov alone knows how to show - into a bad joke about
arrows thrown at a target, with the loss of the court dances and the
charming Farandole for the peasants? (The inclusion of the second act
entr'acte was justified because we had the Mariinsky orchestra playing
magnificently, with a fine but unnamed violinist - worthy heir to Leopold
Auer for whom this music was first written.).
The general run of mime performance, and the supernumeraries who dress the
stage, seemed numb with tedium. The Virsaladze designs - more truncated than
heretofore - are still beautiful, even if the last act shows us a distant
prospect of the casino at Beaulieu rather than Versailles. But the costuming
needs attention: wigs are increasingly improbable except as examples of what
a bright girl can do with cotton wool; some of the court outfits, still worn
with flair, are risible. The production, in sum, is an unworthy frame for
the company's classic style - exquisite in poise and lightness; the shape of
movement ideal in balance and generosity. The work of the corps de ballet
exemplifies these virtues quite as much as the dancing of the soloists. We
watch, and marvel. Academism becomes highest art.
In Thursday's performance by Larissa Lezhnina as Aurora, the dance was true
and lovely. Hers is an interpretation which combines easiest grace with
something gentle. Never badgering her audience with technique, Lezhnina
dances with a dulcet mastery that is irresistible. Line is pure; the
character is youthful; there is something happily engaging in every moment;
here, indeed, is a young princess, with all that implies of aristocratic
means and femininity. There are moments when Lezhnina shows she can command
formidable resources of skill, but everything is dedicated to Petipa's steps
in their purest form. It is an exemplary reading.
Her Prince was Farukh Ruzimatov. The Kirov has taught us how this role may
be grandly danced. Interpretations by Semenyov, by Sokolov (a marvel of
elegance and technical distinction: on his first London appearance he had to
repeat the coda of his variation), and by the angelic Solovyov, were as
near-perfect as makes no difference. Ruzimatov took to the stage in what
looked a sulky impersonation of Nureyev (another great Kirov Prince). Given
his tangled Medusa-locks and his sniffy expression, Aurora might be forgiven
for thinking she had been awakened by Carabosse. Nor did Ruzimatov's dancing
make much of a case for his princely status. I thought it an unlikely
reading.
The dancing of the Fairy soloists and of the corps de ballet was - in spite
of a sense of cramped conditions - distinguished. I record, for
fellow-admirers of Good King Herod, that there was an outburst of smirking
tots in the first act waltz, all of whom should have been in bed hours
before. In fairness, though, I note that on home territory the Kirov's child
cohorts are quite clearly human, and beautifully trained.
The Kirov Ballet is at the Coliseum, London, until July 31. Programming
varies.
</TEXT>
<XX>
