<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / Books: The making of a fool
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEPHEN AMIDON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NOBODY'S FOOL by Richard Russo Chatto &amp; Windus Pounds 15.99, 552 pages
IT IS not easy being nobody's fool. In fact, for Donald 'Sully' Sullivan it
has turned out to be a full time job. For his entire adult life the sometime
construction worker, sometime philosophy student has been able to keep the
residents of North Bath, New York, from making a fool of him. Unfortunately
in the process he has managed to alienate just about everyone he knows.
Richard Russo's remarkable third novel is about the few weeks in Sully's
60th year when he finally decides to let down his guard and let in some of
the people he has been keeping at bay.
For all his headstrong independence, Sully has precious little to show for
himself. He lives in a barely furnished apartment in the house of Miss
Beryl, a common-sensical widow who has had Sully's measure since she taught
him in the eighth grade. Sully's neurotic ex-wife dropped him 30 years
earlier, moving as far uptown as you can in the claustrophobic environs of
North Bath. His son Peter lives in West Virginia, still smarting from
Sully's decision to walk away from him as a boy and avoid the potential cap
and bells of fatherhood. And his married lover, Ruth, has just about had it
with him as well, thinking with some justification that if a man at 60 is
not prepared to settle down then he probably never will.
So Sully spends his time with the few people who will have him - his
woebegone and odoriferous co-worker Rub, the butt of countless jokes; his
drunken, one-legged lawyer Wirf, who tries with scant success to keep Sully
out of trouble; and his womanising boss Carl Roebuck, whose wife Toby is the
true apple of Sully's eye. Their protracted drinking sessions at the local
bar are hilarious set-pieces, scruffy jewels of buffoonery and smart-aleck
dialogue.
Sully's independence is sorely threatened over the Thanksgiving and
Christmas holidays of 1984, however, when Peter returns to town, escaping a
troubled marriage and a ruined career. To his surprise and initial horror,
Sully is forced to be both the father he never was and the grandfather he
hoped never to be, helping Peter and his own troubled son Will land on their
feet. In the process, he comes to terms with the ghost of his abusive
father, Big Jim, whose constant belittlement of the boy Sully might be the
cause of his lifelong pigheadedness.
Nobody's Fool is big, funny and richly human, a garrulous book that button
holes you in the first few pages and does not let you go until it has had
its say. The town of North Bath is a wonderful creation, the sort of place
where Texan investors choose not to build a theme park because, well, the
people there look sort of funny. It is a place of beautiful old houses
occupied by widows who refuse to die simply for the sake of a property boom;
of doomed civic boosters who will run off with S &amp; L funds at the drop of a
hat; of middle-aged Lotharios and their fading cheerleader mistresses. Like
Garrison Keillor, Russo is able to show small-town life warts and all. In
fact, half the time he makes you think it is nothing but warts.
And in Sully Russo has created a character you cannot resist - as long as
you are reading about him and not related to him. He is 'the uncontested
master of the futile gesture' and a 'case study underachiever', the sort of
man people think could have been so much more, though they could not say
exactly what if pressed. But just when the reader is at the point of getting
fatally exasperated with Sully, Russo shows the real pain that has caused
him to be the way he is. Sully's conversion to his own rough and ready form
of responsibility is both comic and strangely moving. In the end, he learns
what most people know and he should have known all along - that everybody
has to be somebody's fool.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P2731 Book Publishing.
</IN>
