<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / Books: Wodehouse meets the mullahs - Summer Fiction
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NICHOLAS BEST
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EAST OF WIMBLEDON by Nigel Williams Faber Pounds 14.99, 374 pages
IN THE KINGDOM OF AIR by Tim Binding Jonathan Cape Pounds 14.99, 374 pages
KISSING THROUGH A PANE OF GLASS by Peter Michael Rosenberg Simon &amp; Schuster
Pounds 14.99, 235 pages
THE CENTRE OF THE LABYRINTH by Philip Lloyd-Bostock Quartet Pounds 16.95,
472 pagews
BRAVE OF Nigel Williams to write a book about English Moslems, poking fun at
the eccentricities of a religion not noted for its sense of humour towards
British novelists. Brave, but not blasphemous, so the mullahs need not be
alarmed. There is nothing in East of Wimbledon to get them issuing fatwas or
burning the book in the streets. It is just a gentle dig at the oddities of
Islam, as exemplified by the activities of a group of Dharjees - loosely
based on a real Shiite sect - who prowl London's better-class suburbs,
threatening death and damnation to anyone who has the temerity to get in
their way.
The plot revolves around Robert Wilson, an unemployed and rather feeble
Englishman who fakes a conversion to Islam in order to get a job at
Wimbledon's Islamic Independent Boys' Day School. The school is run by Mr
Malik, a disgraceful reprobate whose interest in drink and women is not what
a headmaster's ought to be, especially a Moslem headmaster's. Among the
pupils is Hasan, a blind 10-year-old 'prophet' - again based on a real
Islamic character - who the Dharjees believe is destined to appear on earth
one day and save the world.
So far, so Evelyn Waugh. But the author's approach is more PG Wodehouse than
anything, Wodehouse combined with a fair measure of slapstick and farce of
the Carry On kind. There are mad Irishmen here, dog murderers, Moslems with
tea towels on their heads, old ladies helped on their way to Paradise by a
No 33 bus. The Radcliffe Camera triggers a joke about photography, and the
failure of anyone to murder Robert Wilson for a reward of Pounds 10 is
promptly followed by a raising of the blood money to Pounds 12.50, but still
without result.
Williams' humour, in other words, is a little forced in places, rather more
forced than is welcome. He pitches his wit at the undergraduate level and
hits the mark as often as not. But one cannot help feeling that he would
have written a better book if he had suppressed the urge to amuse all the
time and simply allowed the jokes to arise naturally from the writing, as
they surely would have done if he had had enough confidence in himself and
his past achievements to let it flow.
Tim Binding has no past literary achievements to fall back on, being a
first-time author and a former publisher to boot, but he has not let that
stop him. In the Kingdom of Air is a most interesting book, albeit flawed in
one or two respects. It tells the story of a young man growing up on the
Medway, and of his affair with a teenage girl named Stella, who disappears
one night, never to be seen again. The police suspect the young man of her
murder and question him endlessly. However, they have no evidence and let
the case drop. Many years later, the young man's sister spots Stella at a
London railway station and follows her home. Gradually the truth emerges
about Stella's disappearance.
It is an intriguing story, neatly put together, although the structure is
rather too complicated for what is in essence a fairly simple plot. The
author fights shy of dialogue and writes paragraphs of prose that go on for
pages at a time. But he has a definite talent nonetheless, one that will
doubtless serve him well in future years. What a pity he has already wasted
so much of his life as a publisher.
It is not a bad week for first novels. Peter Michael Rosenberg's Kissing
through a Pane of Glass was runner-up for last year's Betty Trask prize - a
greater recommendation than it might at first appear - and is about love, as
Trask awards have to be. In particular, it is about a young man's passion
for a beautiful girl he met in India, a girl with a mysterious past.
The story begins unpromisingly at Sussex University, where the young man is
learning everything he can about sex. Since he is not in the least
good-looking, this is an uphill task. But just when one is thinking that
there is only so much one wants to know about an unattractive youth
searching for sex on the south coast, the story switches to India, where he
has gone after graduation. There he meets the beautiful Liana, who promptly
surrenders her virginity to him within a few hours of their first meeting.
Well, we all have our fantasies. But there is method in the author's
madness, as soon becomes apparent. The madness in fact is Liana's, because
she is seriously disturbed, and it becomes the hero's mission in life to
take care of her and protect her from herself. The story is a moving one,
skilfully told, well worth persevering with after a hesitant start.
Philip Lloyd-Bostock's first novel, The Centre of the Labyrinth, is also his
last, the author having died of Aids seven years ago. Indeed, he was still
working on the book when he died. It is a highly intellectual work -
Lloyd-Bostock was an Oxford don with an interest in semiotics - which begins
by charting the relationship between a beautiful heiress and a homosexual
photographer, and ends not altogether surprisingly with the photographer's
discovery that he has Aids and is going to die.
People in a similar situation may well wish to read the book and empathise.
If they do, they should be warned that it is not a particularly easy read,
partly because the author still had plenty of corrections to make, but
mostly because he wrote like an academic in the first place, which is not
always the best of recommendations for a novelist, even one with as large a
vocabulary as Lloyd-Bostock's.
</TEXT>
