<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / Books: What price a Czar after Communism?
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT CARVER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NICHOLAS II EMPEROR OF ALL THE RUSSIAS by Dominic Lieven John Murray Pounds
19.99, 304 pages
IN FEBRUARY 1991, six months before Communism collapsed, I stood in the
Peter and Paul Cathedral of what was still then Leningrad. There was a large
hole being dug next to the line of tombs holding the remains of Russia's
rulers. 'For Nicholas II,' a fierce young student explained, 'And with God's
help we'll soon see a Czar crowned here again'. At the time this had about
all the apparent likeliness of a Jacobite fulminating in Westminster
Cathedral.
Lievan, an LSE don specialising in late Imperial Russia, has written this
biography in the light of Communism's recent collapse: no longer are the
Romanovs the pariahs they once were. The dustbin of history is now crammed
with the cadavers of former consigners.
There is a certain amount of fresh archive information here but not enough
to justify another biography. The interesting part of the book is the new
perspective and the insights that flow from it. Lievan's last chapter, 'Then
and Now', where he weighs up the Romanovs and Nicholas II in the light of
Communism's collapse, contains stimulating ideas and should have come at the
start of the book. Since capitalism won in the Cold War, the late flowering
of an industrial and mercantile culture under Czarism now looks healthier,
he argues, than the State-run artifices which replaced it under Lenin and
Stalin. The concept of three waves of 'modernism imposed from above' which
Lievan perceives in Russia's history is sound and insightful.
Lievan counters the usual canard about the Empress Alexandra's pro-Germanism
by bringing out the intense Englishness of her character. It was Nicholas
and Alexandra's very lack of Russianness which so alienated them from
fashionable upper-class Petersburg. The pusillanimous refusal of Nicholas's
cousin, George V of England, to grant the deposed Romanovs visas for England
leaves the author with 'a somewhat sour taste In the mouth' - perhaps the
greatest understatement in an understated book.
It was the disastrous Russo-Japanese war which lost the Romanovs their
autocracy and their legitimacy, and the even more catastrophic First War
which destroyed both them and their dynasty. Nicholas was certainly at fault
in precipitating the former, but the latter he saw clearly as a grave menace
and tried to avoid with all his power.
This chapter of history is by no means closed. The Yeltsin era may yet come
to be seen as Kerensky-in-reverse, a republican interregnum between
Communism and a full-blown return to Czarist-style, right wing, Russian
nationalist autocracy. Many would say Yeltsin already has many of the
hallmarks of a new, absolutist Emperor in embryo.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
