</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / The Property Market: Market progress slows, say agents -
Cadogan's Place
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GERALD CADOGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE PROPERTY market's progress slowed in June, with net sales 5.8 per cent
down compared with May, the Corporate Estate Agents Property Index reports.
Contracts exchanged rose marginally, but are still down in comparison with
March, which has been the peak month for business in 1993.
Confidence in the government was stronger then than now. And even if the
recovery is under way, the spectre of higher taxes in the Budget in the
autumn is still a dampener.
Estate agent John D. Wood reports that its February-April quarter was
profitable but the previous six months had been the worst for more than 20
years. It had a pre-tax loss for the year until April 30 of Pounds 291,000,
down from Pounds 497,000 on the previous year.
Savills, however, has turned a Pounds 1.44m loss into a Pounds 2.86m profit,
on the year to April 30, selling twice as many houses in London in the
second half-year as it had the year before.
THE ORANGERY, in Mamhead Park, seven miles from Exeter, is an octagonal
pleasure-dome said to be by Robert Adam.
Originally it was a temple or water house. In the last century it became a
gardener's cottage, but now it is a most sophisticated rural delight with
two bedrooms, in 46 acres with views over the Exe estuary. Knight Frank &amp;
Rutley, in Exeter, (0392-433033) will sell it by informal tender on August
12. The guide price is Pounds 325,000.
Also new on the market is a thatched cottage by John Nash, a picturesque
change from his stucco cottages in Regent's Park in London. Home Farm at
Burley on the Hill near Oakham in Rutland is on high ground and has five
bedrooms, a walled garden and a thatched game larder, and the original plans
are in the Leicestershire Records Office. Humphrey Repton commissioned this
curio of architectural history as part of his work at the big house. Clegg
Kennedy Drew in Stamford (0780-52788) offers it at Pounds 375,000.
BUCKLAND HOUSE, near Faringdon, in Oxfordshire, is a Georgian villa built
for the Throckmorton family by the famous Bath architects, John Wood father
and son, on strict Palladian lines, with a central block linked by passages
to octagons.
One was the library and the other served as a Roman Catholic chapel. The
house has fine plasterwork and chimney pieces, and a big white-tiled area
below-stairs, but will be costly to repair. The purchaser might wish to
restore its 18th century aspect by demolishing the parts added for a planned
visit by Edward VII, which never took place. The price for two lots is
Pounds 1m, from Cluttons (0865-793900).
Next door is the Tudor Manor House turned into Strawberry Hill Gothic-style
stables by the Throckmortons in the late 18th century. Cluttons hopes for
Pounds 275,000 but, as with the big house, redoing it will be expensive. You
can walk straight from the downstairs rooms into the loose boxes without
going outside.
IN BEVERLY HILLS, California, 822 North Roxbury Drive was the home of
Marlene Dietrich. The solidly built Art Deco building was built in 1928 and
influenced by styles from ancient Egypt (in the aftermath of finding king
Tutankhamun's tomb). The director Joseph von Steinberg chose it for her in
1931, complete with a very large living room, a large kitchen, a large pool
and a cellar that held 5000 bottles. Rita Hayworth lived there later.
Sotheby's International Realty in New York (800-848-2541) and Stan Herman
and Stephen Shapiro in Beverly Hills (310-274-9494) are agents. The price is
Dollars 2.495m. (Pounds 1.66m).
</TEXT>
