<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / The Property Market: Mooring charges
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THOSE WHO spend their leisure time on the water quickly find there are
plenty of hidden extras such as insurance, supplies (including paint for the
boat), repairs, membership of a club, and harbour dues.
Berthing charges are probably the heftiest item, though. Swinging moorings
on a buoy in the harbour or estuary are cheaper than renting a berth in a
marina; but for such a lovely spot as the Beaulieu river in Hampshire, they
are still pricy, with an annual charge of Pounds 42 a foot plus VAT. For a
typical 30ft boat, that is Pounds 1,480 before you raise a sail.
Marinas are dearer, even though some prices are reduced slightly from last
year and could come down further in 1994. Lymington Yacht Haven in Hampshire
charges Pounds 2,908 for a 30ft boat, to include everything except
electricity, while Swanwick at Hamble, Hampshire, is Pounds 2,820 (at Pounds
80 a foot, down from Pounds 82). Brighton Marina is cheaper, giving a 20 per
cent discount on the list price of Pounds 225 a metre (including VAT) which
makes Pounds 1,710 for the 30-footer (9.5 metres).
On the Isle of Wight, Cowes Yacht Haven has a two-tier system, with
provisional charges for October 1993 to March 1994 of Pounds 45 a metre, and
for April to September 1994 of Pounds 170 a metre, both plus VAT.
</TEXT>
<XX>
