<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / How to Spend It: Office gossip, how the power brokers work
and play - Santa Raymond, a practising architect and interior designer,
looks at the offices that three movers and shakers have created / Lynne
Franks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SANTA RAYMOND
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LYNNE FRANKS, doyenne of the public relations world, believes that colour is
important.
She explains that the purple of the paint work and sofa in her office is the
colour of spiritual receiving, and that the pale green of the walls provides
energy. The frieze of white convolvulus, after Georgia O'Keefe, which runs
from side to side of the office was suggested by 'dowsing' to balance energy
levels.
Franks aims for a relaxed and comfortable place where clients will unwind,
colleagues feel able to express their anxieties, and her charitable
interests may be discussed profitably. She talks of the atmosphere of her
office conveying the 'balanced woman, with career and family life in
equilibrium'; of it being a place in which to 'be centred, and feel good
in.'
It is a high room, top-lit and without windows. It could be a daunting
space. However, with designer Ben Kelly she has made an environment which is
stimulating, friendly and relaxing.
She has no formal desk but uses a glass-topped table on an antique stand
pushed into the corner. She talks with people sitting on one of two sofas:
the day I visited there was a terracotta vase of catkins on the coffee
table. A glass screen by Danny Lane stands behind, and the walls are covered
with family photographs.
Personal and professional mementos are displayed on a wooden shelf running
beneath the frieze.
It is very much a living-office, without a computer terminal or paper
storage and with just a refrigerator sitting against the wall. I asked
Franks whether the lighting, from translucent orbs hanging from the ceiling,
provided the right atmosphere at night. She said she was not there then, so
it did not matter.
She uses the boardroom for formal meetings, sitting on an orange, scarlet or
fuchsia Arne Jacobsen chair at a glass-topped table by Tom Dixon,
asymmetrical on a miniature space frame.
Everywhere Kelly has used colour and materials in exciting ways, converting
this garage in London's Harrow Road into a corporate office which impresses
such clients as Coca-Cola, Lloyds Bank or the pop singer Annie Lennox.
The door to Lynne Franks's office is never closed, and for much of the time
she is out on the floor with her account executives.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P7389 Business Services, NEC.
</IN>
<XX>
