<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / How to Spend It: Office gossip, how the power brokers work
and play - Santa Raymond, a practising architect and interior designer,
looks at the offices that three movers and shakers have created / Gary
Withers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SANTA RAYMONG
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GARY WITHERS' office is an eyrie in the apex of the Imagination building in
London's Store Street, over the front door. It has views across to Tottenham
Court Road and towards the University of London's Senate House, and a
balcony at the back overlooks the airy atrium. The pitched roof is glazed,
with light controlled by venetian blinds.
Withers's professional life is very varied. One day he might talk to graphic
or interior designers and architects, the next he may see writers or film
makers about projects ranging from promoting Ford cars to building a castle
at EuroDisney. This complexity is reflected in his working space. From the
double-height living area a spiral staircase leads up to a working gallery.
Here files are piled high, overflowing on to the floor: 'A secretary's
nightmare, but all in current use.' Conceptual work, internal meetings, and
dictation take place up here.
Downstairs is used for more formal meetings, some client presentations, and
entertaining.
At night the lights - low-voltage spots and up-lighters - can be turned
right down to give 'a quite different atmosphere with really moody
lighting.' A fire burns within the marble fireplace and there is a Bechstein
baby grand. There is a complicated sound system, but no computer: 'I can't
stand computers,' says Withers, 'though of course the rest of the building
is full of them.'
Windows here, as elsewhere in the building, can be opened and heating is
surprisingly by night storage heaters: 'Cheaper to install. Cheaper to run.'
The furnishings are eclectic, a mixture of ancient and modern, chosen by
Withers himself with extraordinary speed.
The cool functionalism of chairs by Charles Eames and tables by Eileen Gray
is contrasted with ornate antiques, carved and gilded mirror and side
tables, marble bases and decorative flambeaux from France. With black and
white photographs on the walls (some in-house and some by Mapplethorpe),
black sofas (copies of some at Blenheim) and black tables, the only colour
is from some original sketches for a 1930s clothes catalogue in gouache and
charcoal.
There is a nice rhythm between a round timber mirror over the fireplace
(carved by Norman Simpson), the circular window (externally the fulcrum of
the facade), walnuts in a great glass jar, and some oversize spheres of
lavender (by Robert Day). Colour in the rest of the building comes from
photographs of projects all over the place. Otherwise, colour is restrained:
white walls, beech and chrome elements, dark grey carpets, grey
workstations, black files.
Architects, Herron Associates, designed the conversion of this building,
originally a Victorian school, in close collaboration with Withers. It
illustrates perfectly the effect of a good partnership between a dedicated
client and talented designer.
These are exciting and practical interiors which serve well the needs of the
organisation while showing clearly the ethos of this design and
communications company: flamboyant, theatrical and yet timeless; simple and
direct, underlined with quality.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P7389 Business Services, NEC.
</IN>
