<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / How to Spend It: Office gossip - how the power brokers work
and play / Santa Raymond, a practising architect and interior designer,
looks at the offices that three movers and shakers have created
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SANTA RAYMOND
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GARY WITHERS, of the public relations company Imagination, Lord Young,
chairman of Cable and Wireless, and Lynne Franks, the public relations
consultant, all work in offices which express clearly the culture of their
businesses as well as their personalities and preferences.
Although the businesses with which Franks, Withers and Young are involved
are technologically sophisticated, the primary work of all three is
face-to-face communication.
This is reflected in the design of their offices. None of them is setting
out to impress from behind large desks. Each office is comfortable and
unpretentious, a place in which people may be encouraged to talk openly and
effectively.
Withers is himself a designer by trade, Franks has worked with her designer,
Ben Kelly, over many years, and though Lord Young only came in on the design
process when he joined the company half way through the building works he
has 'no hang ups about talking with designers.'
Each has had a highly creative relationship with their designer, and for
each the result has been an office which fits them as individuals, and which
portrays to colleagues and visitors the essence of their company culture.
Here, in a nutshell, is how their offices help them succeed . . .
</TEXT>
