<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / Food &amp; Drink: Appetisers
</HEADLINE>
<DATELINE>
   By EDMUND PENNING-ROWSELL, GILES MACDONOGH and JANCIS ROBINSON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FOR THE fifth year in succession Champagne will be faced with a large
vintage and, unless bad weather intervenes, a very good one. It will be
picked several weeks earlier than usual - within the first 10days of
September. In view of the very high level of unsold stocks, the price of
grapes is likely to be lower than last year, which will be decided between
merchants and growers at the end of next month as a recommended figure,
perhaps as low as FFr20 a kilo for the top commune grapes.
EDMUND PENNING-ROWSELL
Following the decision taken by the EC on June 1 to tax beer at 'factory
gate' strength as opposed to the cumbersome system of original gravity
(which measures potential alcohol), Camra's monthly journal What's Brewing
reports a move made by at least two major brewers to avoid higher duty by
reducing the alcoholic strength of their ales and lagers.
This could also involve an increase in the levels of unfermented malt sugar
in the beer in an attempt to disguise any resulting flavour imbalance. Those
chiefly involved to date are Bass and Courage. The following brands are
affected: Webster's Yorkshire Bitter, Wilson's Original Bitter,
Worthington's Best Bitter and Holsten Pils lager.
One brewer which has not gone in for this sort of thing is Britain's oldest,
Shepherd Neame, in Faversham, Kent. It has not only maintained its good
reputation for cask-conditioned ales, but also been at the forefront of the
revival of good bottle-conditioned beers.
The latest to arrive is Spitfire, a bitter originally brewed to celebrate
the 50th anniversary of the Battle of Britain.
It is a suitably hoppy ale, given Kent's position as the centre of Britain's
hop-farming business.
Spitfire is available in 500cl bottles from Shepherd Neame pubs, priced
around Pounds 1.82, and from select branches of Safeway at about Pounds
1.45. The beer contains yeast and should be poured with care.
GILES MACDONOGH
Owners of the Stratford label blend California wine have been able to offer
better value West Coast wine than most. Majestic, in particular, has been a
good source of their Zinfandel, Chardonnay and Cabernet. But the best buy to
date must be their Pinot Noir, Pounds 4.89 from better branches of Victoria
Wine until the end of this month. I was fooled into pricing it several
pounds higher when served this juicy, rich red. A second bottle might cloy,
but the first should delight both palate and pocket.
JANCIS ROBINSON
Many wine drinkers are intrigued by the idea of becoming wine tasters, but
are reluctant to expose themselves to public ridicule. The Wine Society of
Stevenage (0438-740222) has the perfect answer: eight very different
six-bottle tasting cases which come with a sensible booklet, How to Taste,
tasting sheets, and detailed notes on each case's theme and the individual
wines. Prices range from Pounds 34.50 for the basic assortment, to Pounds
65.75 for six half bottles of sweet wine which constitute 'the best of the
bunch'. There is a Pounds 20 life membership fee.
JANCIS ROBINSON
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
