<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / Food &amp; Drink: Sleeping beauties - Jancis Robinson unearths
some classics at bargain prices / Wine
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JANCIS ROBINSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THANK GOODNESS some wine merchants are being pro-active about this
recession. Too many British merchants have been concentrating solely on
improving their range under Pounds 5 a bottle, often rather belatedly - 'Now
let's see, where is this place Oc?' But some have been alert enough to
realise that some of the best wine buys around are of classic wines
desperate to find a buyer.
The most obvious examples of this have been vintage ports, particularly
1983s and 1985s, which have been going for a song at auction and have been
retailed by the single bottle for hardly a couple of songs. Oddbins has had
the delicious Smith Woodhouse 1983 at just Pounds 11.99 a bottle, not much
more than when it was released.
But perhaps the richest hunting ground for fine wine bargains at the moment
is Burgundy, where both negociants and individual domaines are suffering a
severe case of post-opportunism.
Throughout the 1980s these sheltered producers of prototype Chardonnay and
Pinot Noir could hardly keep up with demand. Prices, and yields, rose
accordingly. Many wines, especially whites, came less to express place than
grape variety, contrary to the spirit of France's appellation controlee law.
Meanwhile, the rest of the world's growers of these grapes made rapid
strides in producing wines with more finesse and integrity, but at much
lower prices.
The result is that in too many cases burgundy became over-priced and
under-expressive in comparison with its counterparts elsewhere (particularly
parts of California, Australia and New Zealand, although the New World is
yet to rival Burgundy at its best).
Even more importantly than this, burgundy (a bit like champagne) is
associated with the extravagances of the 1980s, and stocks in the Burgundy
region have been sleeping beautifully, awaiting a wake-up call from the
princely likes of Tony Mason of Majestic, Graham Chidgey of Laytons, and
Robin Crameri of Peatlings. All three have made notable raids on the cellars
of Burgundy, although Chidgey is a particularly veteran campaigner.
Majestic is selling through its wine warehouses 3,000 cases of growers'
burgundies at prices that would have been unthinkable this time last year,
although some of the examples I tasted exhibited some of the faults of some
growers' burgundies: an earthy lack of fruit. Nevertheless, neither their
Bourgogne Rouge 1991, from Mongeard-Mugneret, nor their Bourgogne Rouge
1989, from the Maconnais Domaine de la Chapelle, are to be sniffed at when
offered at Pounds 5.99 a bottle - and the Chablis 1991 is a very respectable
mouthful for Pounds 4.99.
Chidgey has found a clutch of genuinely interesting white burgundies under
Pounds 10, currently available either at Laytons, of London NW1
(071-388-5081), or by the bottle from Andre Simon shops in central London.
Jean-Marie Guffens, the talented and idiosyncratic Belgian whose sky-high
Pouilly-Fuisses have long been sold by Laytons, now has his own negociant
house, Verget, buying in grapes from Cote d'Or vineyards.
Verget's Bourgogne Blanc 1991 is a fascinating hotchpotch of leftovers. The
subtlety and depth of flavour transmitted by fermenting lesser wine on the
lees from various famous vineyards can be tasted.
And Laytons' own Pouilly-Fuisse 1992, made in Ropiteau's cellars, is
tailor-made for those who complain that the punch has gone out of white
burgundy. Both wines sell for about Pounds 9 for a single bottle, or about
Pounds 8 as part of a case.
Perhaps most enterprising is Peatlings' special offer of domaine burgundy,
bottled in Bury St Edmunds, Suffolk. In an uncharacteristically snazzy
booklet, the wine division of Greene King, the East Anglian brewers, is
offering four red 1991s and three white 1992s at extremely competitive
prices. Here is a rare opportunity for the humble wine drinker to benefit
from boardroom machinations (as Bernard Pinault has done by buying Ch Latour
so advantageously from Allied Lyons).
The wines are the produce of eminently respectable Burgundian sources and
taste delightfully frank and true - most of them genuinely of the terrain.
I found the best white by quite a margin was the Chassagne Montrachet 1992
from Michel Colin's own vines, and was thrilled by all three 1991 reds from
Lucien Boillot: the charming Volnay at Pounds 9.99 for the next year or two,
and the premier cru Volnay, Les Angles at Pounds 11.99 and the
Gevrey-Chambertin at Pounds 9.99 for keeping. The Gevrey is probably the
best buy of all. Peatlings, which has a shop in London EC1 as well as 26 in
East Anglia, is also offering free cellarage of all wines bought through
them - a not inconsiderable incentive.
There are also bargains to be had higher up the scale, and not just in
Burgundy. Farr Vintners, of London SW1 (071-828-1960), has been selling
Bonneau de Martray's famous Corton Charlemagne 1987 at the silly price of
Pounds 150 a case, and has a number of claret bargains too. Meanwhile rivals
Cave Cru Classe, of London SE1 (071-378-8579), has a special offer of
Domaine Ponsot's highly acclaimed 1990 red burgundies, and rivals Turville
Valley Wines, of Great Missenden (02406-8818), and Wilkinson Vintners, of
London NW3 (071-267-1945), are also busy paring prices to the bone.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
