<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / Sport: Irish chase a Cup that cheers - Yachting
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEITH WHEATLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INGENUITY has been the key to the 1993 Champagne Mumm Admiral's Cup. When
the unofficial world championship of yacht racing begins off Cowes next
Thursday, it will be a small, devious field that crosses the start line.
Take the Irish team, for example.
Ireland has been in and out of the AC over the years but never won the
trophy. Thanks to Sydney-based businessman John Storey, the Emerald Isle,
which has previously tended to export its sailing talent, is co-favourite to
take the cup.
Several years ago Storey encountered Harold Cudmore, the Cork-born
professional who skippered Britain's bid for the America's Cup in 1986.
Cudmore showed him that by chartering top boats at exactly the right moment,
one could both block the opposition and 'ride good horses.' Stir in the
visceral willingness of Irishmen who ply their trade in other countries to
fight for the Auld Sod, and one has a winning combination. The first
consequence was victory for Storey/Cudmore/Ireland in the 1992 Southern
Cross series in Australia.
Bitten by the bug, Storey moved on with the svengali Cudmore at his elbow.
Their master-stroke for this campaign was to buy the world champion
two-tonner Shockwave from Kiwi owner Neville Crichton.
Under the procedures devised for the 1993 Admiral's Cup, the points scored
by each team's two-tonner will probably be crucial. As the middle-sized
component of each team, between the one-tonner and 50ft yachts, they should
be competitive across the whole range of conditions. With only the best two
results per team from each race scoring, this is important.
As a class this is likely to be the swansong for the two-tonners. Numbers
are declining and good ones have been stalked and hunted across the world by
would-be Admiral's Cup captains. Britain could not be certain of having a
team until some appallingly delicate negotiations with the Turkish owner of
Prodzza (the former Unibank, of Denmark) were concluded.
Cudmore's 'stroke' - as the Irish would put it - with Shockwave had a
beautiful symmetry to it. As well as giving his team the most powerful
platform possible, New Zealand's sailors were unable to find an adequate
two-tonner and are not competing at Cowes. They have always provided
formidable opposition in previous events. With only eight countries
competing, the field is smaller than since the early 1970s.
Cudmore, sailing for his own country for the first time since 1979, will
skipper the one-tonner Jameson I (ex Fram XI, owned by King Harald of
Norway). Jameson II (ex-Shockwave) is steered by Gordon Maguire and the
50-footer (Jameson III, aka Heaven Can Wait) is under the control of
ex-Whitbread skipper Joe English.
Once this formidable collection of personnel and hardware was assembled,
'King Harold of Cowes', as Cudmore is sometimes known, was able to go to
Jameson, the leading Irish whiskey brand, and secure team sponsorship.
Cudmore had to act like an independent film producer: juggling the studio,
the stars and the bank until they are all safely to hand, pointing in the
same direction.
Britain has had to go through broadly the same process to assemble a team.
It may be no coincidence that team captain Graham Walker has had Cudmore
skipper a good number of his racing yachts over the past decade. Once Walker
acquired the 50ft Indulgence (ex-Juno) earlier this year, it was a question
of building the rest of a team around that platform.
'I'm sure that despite a low number of teams this is going to be the most
competitive Admiral's Cup ever,' said Walker. With a dearth of top-level
racing available around the world, there is absolutely no doubt that the
best boats and top crews are gathered in Cowes. However, Walker is confident
of Britain's chances of regaining the trophy they last won in 1989.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>IEZ  Ireland, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P7941 Sports Clubs, Managers, and Promoters.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>NEWS  General News.
</TP>
