<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / Special Report on Second Cars: Checks and balances - Buying
second-hand
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEN GOODING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MOST people who buy a private car new know that its value will drop by
Pounds 2,000 to Pounds 3,000 even before they drive it away from the
showroom. That is what happens when the first name is entered in the
registration document. So, it makes financial sense to buy a 'nearly-new'
car instead.
Buying a car is also about image, though - particularly, the image of
ourselves which we wish to convey to others. In the boom years of the 1980s
the desire to project the right image often took precedence over financial
common sense but the recession has produced a cannier consumer who is more
concerned about value.
A recent survey by RAC Motoring Services revealed that more than 60 per cent
of those questioned were considering buying a used car next time 'to save
money.' But this cannier consumer is having an impact on the used car market
already. Prices of desirable, low-mileage models have been rising steadily
this year.
Andrew Wilkinson, senior editor of the CAP Black Book - used by the car
trade as a guide to prices - explains that there is a shortage of cars,
caused partly by the dramatic downturn in new vehicle registrations since
1990 and the tendency during the recession for companies to keep their fleet
cars longer.
He says that ex-fleet cars, even those with high mileages, are 'making very
strong money' just now. And the poor condition of some of these vehicles is
not deterring buyers from paying relatively high prices.
'Even executive and high-performance cars, which in the recent past have
been out of favour and difficult for a dealer to sell at anything but low
prices, have now made a comeback,' Wilkinson adds. Only the 'hot hatch'
models have not been following the rest of the market - although, even here,
prices have stabilised.
Buyers are more confident about used cars because it has become clear that
modern vehicles last well and tolerate high mileages. Neither is rusty
bodywork the problem it was, as manufacturers have taken to using much more
galvanised steel and better production techniques.
A nearly-new car today will usually come with a manufacturer's transferable
rust warranty. While these are complicated and hardly worth the paper on
which they are printed, they are an indication that makers are taking the
matter seriously.
Many cars have transferable manufacturers' warranties, offering genuine
protection against major defects. Some Japanese makes are offering
warranties for three years or 60,000 miles. Dealers often offer warranties
when selling used cars, but some are better than others. If the dealer
offers warranties that do not cover electronics and other expensive items,
you could probably do better buying one from an insurance company.
There are always some risks associated with buying used cars. Astonishingly,
there is no totally reliable way of proving who owns a vehicle. You cannot
rely on the registration document; it shows only the 'registered keeper,'
who might not be the owner. It could be a leased company car. And if you buy
a car that turns out to be stolen, in nearly every case you have no right to
keep it.
HPI Autodata, during test marketing early in 1993, was asked by more than
10,000 people if the cars they were about to buy had a 'record.' Searches
showed there was cause for concern in one-third of cases. The vehicle was
not what it appeared, had been reported as stolen or at risk from theft, was
the subject of an accident write-off, or had outstanding finance.
HPI has data on millions of cars, provided by insurance companies and
finance houses throughout the UK. Recently, it went national with its
information service. Instant data, followed by written confirmation, is
available on used cars registered after August 1986 for a Pounds 15 fee by
phoning 0722-422 422 between 8 am and 8 pm Monday-Saturday.
Another way a buyer can protect himself is to ask for the invoice that the
seller received when buying the car. (In this connection, it is also a good
idea to keep safely the paperwork you obtain). Other documents might help,
such as MOT test certificates and servicing documents.
In any case, a would-be buyer should ask for documents giving the full
service history of a used car. This helps combat another big risk - that the
car might have been 'clocked' (ie, had its odometer turned back). Trading
standards officers estimate that this has happened to 20 per cent of used
cars; the lower the recorded mileage, the higher the price that can be
charged.
Villains are also getting better at repairing cars written off by insurance
companies, welding two or three bodies together to make one so expertly that
only an experienced engineer can spot the deception. The best protection
against this fraud is to ask for an inspection by the Automobile Association
(0345-500 610) or the Royal Automobile Club (0800-333 660). Charges start at
about Pounds 100 but vary considerably depending on the size and complexity
of the vehicle.
The Consumers' Association offers an action pack on buying a used car. This
costs Pounds 4.45 by mail order from PO Box 44, Hertford Z, SG14 1SH, or at
the Which? bookshop, 361 Euston Road, London. It is available for Pounds 9
at other bookshops.
</TEXT>
<XX>
