<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / Special Report on Second Cars: Bring on the Twingo -
Practical runabouts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STUART MARSHALL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHERE IS the second car that is, above all, practical? A car cheap to buy
and run; compact, yet roomy; and cleanable inside and out, if not with a
hosepipe, then with a bucket and sponge?
There used to be one: the Renault 4. But, having made 8,135,424 of them (two
of which I bought) in 32 years, Renault knocked it on the head last
December. Nothing like it exists now, although the Fiat Panda (also nearing
the end of the road) could have been. It is cheap, square and sensible but
not quite long enough as a load-carrier. And it was never made with four
passenger doors - a must if children are to be stowed away easily and
elderly passengers allowed to enter and leave with dignity.
The Renault 4, like the Citroen 2CV that preceded it, was created for a
France that no longer exists. It was a country populated by peasant farmers
who had been weaned only recently from horses and carts. They wanted a
cheap, simple car that would stand being driven overloaded on bad roads or
across fields.
The 2CV was an unbreakable runabout but the R4 was a better load-carrier -
its tailgate and flat floor were bigger. Like the 2CV, it had nothing
hanging down underneath and very soft, long-travel suspension.
The soft suspension also meant that it rolled on corners like a
flat-bottomed boat in a beam sea but never fell over. I cannot say it was
very fast, but it would hold 65mph on a motorway and even gallop up to an
indicated 80mph, downhill with a following wind.
Its unorthodox gear lever sprouting from the fascia put off many prospective
British buyers, but it worked in the same way as one on the floor. Its great
advantage was leaving the front of the car free of any obstruction. When you
parked, you slid across the seats - lovely soft ones they were, too - and
stepped straight on to the pavement.
The heater was adequate and the fresh-air ventilation primitive but
effective. You opened two large vents in the fascia and bucketfuls of air
rushed in. Wire mesh like a kitchen strainer removed the larger insects and
small birds.
A huge fabric sun-roof was a cheap R4 extra. Open, you could carry long
poles or a ladder - on a fine day, at any rate. Closed, it was leak-proof in
a thunderstorm (or a car wash). And because it was tall, there was enough
room in a Renault 4 for dustbins - even old-fashioned milk churns - to stand
upright. What would not go in could hang out.
Stricter crash-safety requirements finished off the Renault 4. A 32-year-old
design based on a strong, load-bearing platform with a flimsy, lightweight
body could not crumple in the controlled, impact-absorbing way regulations
now demand.
Perhaps buyers are too sophisticated now to appreciate the merits of an
ugly, if practical, car. And since it must be at least 10 years since I
drove a Renault 4, maybe I would find it unacceptably basic as a semi-rural
runabout. But there must be a place for a really simple, roomy car today.
The idea of one lives on at Renault. Star of the 1992 Paris motor show was
its Twingo, a brilliant 'one box' (no bonnet or boot) design with styling
overtones of the Renault Espace but aimed at the broad base of the car
market. Although not as long as the dear old R4 and only a three-door, it is
roomier inside than it looks. That is because its cross-mounted engine takes
up far less space than the 4's fore-and-aft engine plus gearbox stuck out in
front.
Renault is not sure if the Twingo will come to Britain. I reckon it would be
the UK's loss (and Renault's) if it did not.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>FRZ  France, EC.
</CN>
