<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / Special Report on Second Cars: Spoiled for choice - Load
carriers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STUART MARSHALL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
YOU HAVE a young family, dogs, or both. Perhaps, as a keen gardener, you
need to carry loads of rockery stone. Or you haunt furniture auctions,
hoping for bargains. Whichever the case, you need a roomy estate car.
There was a time when, if a Mercedes-Benz 200-300T, Volvo 240/740/940,
Renault Savanna or Vauxhall Carlton suited neither your pocket nor your
requirements, you were stuck. But, within the past year or two, Ford's
Granada (Scorpio) estate has made a welcome (if belated) reappearance;
Citroen's champion weight-lifter, the XM estate, was introduced; and two
beefy Germans - the Audi 100 and BMW 5-Series Touring, the latter an estate
car in all but name - joined the load-carrying ranks.
More recently, yet more have arrived. Mitsubishi's Australian-built,
front-wheel driven, three-litre Sigma has a huge amount of interior space
and combines US-style smoothness with an almost Germanic feeling of strength
and swiftness. Toyota's Camry luxury estate car was developed and is being
produced in the US from which - like Honda's agreeable Accord estate - it is
exported to Britain. And one of the best all-rounders for space and
refinement (as well as secure handling) is the new Volvo 850 estate with
front-wheel drive.
Sadly, the genuine seven-seat estate car - where everyone faces forward and
which has a realistic amount of space for their luggage - is a disappearing
breed. The splendid Peugeot 505 and Citroen CX Familiale models are no more,
though a Renault Savanna with seven front-facing seats is still around.
Several large estates, among them the much underrated Rover Montego and
various Volvos, can be had with seven seats but the rearmost bench faces
backward. When in use, it is suitable only for children up to the age of 12
and takes up all the luggage space. This, too, is the snag with
multi-purpose vehicles (MPVs) such as the Renault Espace and Nissan Serena.
Because recreational 4 x 4s like the Range Rover, Land Rover Discovery and
Mitsubishi Shogun are massively broad-shouldered does not mean they have
huge amounts of cargo space. They do not. The Range Rover is the worst
because its enormous spare wheel is stowed internally; the others do at
least have it bolted on to the back door.
Bought new, large estate cars can be fairly pricy. A Mercedes-Benz 240T
starts at Pounds 23,400, an Audi 100 at Pounds 19,170, and a BMW 5-Series
Touring Pounds 21,800. Ford's Granada estate (from Pounds 17,916), the
Renault Savanna (remarkably, from only Pounds 10,870 for a 1.7-litre), the
Vauxhall Carlton (from Pounds 15,570) and the Volvo 240 (from Pounds 13,395
for a soon-to-disappear Torslanda) are among the best, and least
capital-intensive, buys.
Those looking for second-hand purchases find that large estates hold their
prices better than saloons. Two for which to look out are the Citroen XM and
Volvo 940 2.4SE turbo-diesels (Pounds 20,465 and Pounds 20,745 respectively
when new). For a combination of price, space, weight-shifting ability and
fuel economy, they have no peers.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
