<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / Briefcase, Q&amp;A: VAT 'fraud' by stores
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
HAVING SPENT much time working abroad, I now have frequent opportunities to
host numerous overseas visitors, whom I naturally encourage to spend freely
in our shops.
To my extreme embarrassment, however, I find that some of our major stores
have a policy which appears to defraud overseas residents of some of the VAT
amount that the tax legislation entitles them to.
This is done by making an administrative charge, or by refusing to make any
refund other than through a third party who, in turn, deducts an
administrative fee from the VAT amount. Can visitors insist on a refund of
the full VAT amount?
Suppliers of goods are not obliged to operate the VAT refund scheme but, if
they do, they have to comply with the conditions of the scheme. No doubt,
some take the view that, because of the extra work involved, they should
make a charge for operating the scheme. Some retailers use refund companies
to make the refund arrangements.
If an administrative fee is to be charged, the retailer should explain this
clearly to the customer. There is no question of the full amount of VAT not
being refunded in appropriate cases. This does not mean that a retailer
cannot make a charge for operating the refund scheme. The rules are set out
in HM Customs and Excise Notice 704, which you can obtain from your local
VAT office.
No legal responsibility can be accepted by the Financial Times for the
answers given in these columns. All enquiries will be answered by post as
soon as possible.
</TEXT>
