<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / Finance and The Family: How sport can damage the national
health - Injuries to amateurs and loss of production total nearly Pounds 1bn
each year. But you can insure against disaster
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SPORT is supposed to make you healthier but the number of people limping
back from skiing holidays, or appearing with an arm in a sling after a
squash match, can give the opposite impression.
A study by Sheffield University's medical school estimated that 8m days were
taken off work every year in England and Wales because of amateur sporting
injuries. Recurrent injuries accounted for another 3m days off. The study
put the cost of lost production and treatment for all of these injuries at
almost Pounds 1bn a year.
Researchers found that while more than a quarter of injuries came from
soccer, the most risky amateur sport was rugby, with 54 significant injuries
for every 1,000 occasions of play compared with three per 1,000 in swimming.
Another risk faced by amateur sportsmen is being sued for damages - say, if
a golfer injures someone with a bad slice off the tee or a cricketer damages
property with a towering six of the Botham variety. But insurance is
available for all these eventualities; in fact, you might be covered already
without realising it.
Many sports groups, teams and clubs have insurance covering all their
members for accidents, whether to themselves or others. But such cover tends
to provide fairly low pay-outs, so you might find it prudent to take out
another policy, either as a top-up with the same insurer or separately.
If you have a personal accident or permanent health insurance policy
already, you might find it covers injuries from the milder sports. But these
policies often exclude horse, car or motor cycle racing, mountaineering,
potholing, flying (as a pilot) and winter sports. Some may exclude 'violent'
sports like rugby or karate or insist on special terms for them, such as
higher premiums or a lower level of cover.
Winter sports can be covered most easily with a travel insurance policy  -
unless you indulge often, in which case an individual sports insurance
policy could be worthwhile.
A number of specialist insurers offer personal accident policies for one
specific sport, often through an arrangement with its national controlling
body. Some also cover sports equipment for theft and damage under the same
policy. Ask your organisation about any scheme it might have.
If you are an all-rounder who prefers to take part in a number of different
activities, it could be worth your while to examine a policy of the type
offered by Crispin Speers and Amsport, a subsidiary of Norex. This divides
sport into three risk levels.
You take out insurance at the level appropriate for your most dangerous
activity; this then covers you for any other activity in the same or a lower
category.
Crispin Speers' (071-480-5083) amateur sports policy can be taken out for
individuals or teams of up to 20 people. It divides a list of several dozen
sports into three risk categories.
The lowest includes badminton, golf, rowing and squash. Football, polo,
martial arts and equestrian sports are rated medium risk; while rugby,
American football, mountaineering and motor racing are high risk.
The premiums are calculated in units of Pounds 100, and the amount of cover
for each depends on the risk category. For an individual in a low-risk
sport, Pounds 100 would buy accidental death and dismemberment cover of
Pounds 25,000, permanent total disablement cover of Pounds 50,000, and
temporary total disablement of Pounds 100 a week.
For a high-risk sport, the same premium would buy Pounds 10,000 of
accidental death and dismemberment cover, Pounds 20,000 of permanent total
disablement, and Pounds 50 a week for temporary total disablement. A maximum
of 10 units can be taken out, but Crispin Speers does not offer liability
cover.
Amsport's (071-895-9950) Gameplan policy for individuals lists 102 sports in
three risk categories. The list is similar to that of Crispin Speers but the
companies take a different view of some activities. Amsport defines
water-skiing as high risk but Crispin Speers rates it as low.
Cover comes in gold, silver or bronze versions. Gold cover provides a weekly
benefit of Pounds 100; hospital benefit of Pounds 30 a night; dental fees of
Pounds 275; physiotherapy fees of Pounds 300, Pounds 37,500 if you should
lose a hand, foot, arm, eye or leg, or as a death benefit; and Pounds 75,000
if you should lose both of any of them, or for permanent total disablement.
There is also Pounds 1m personal liability insurance and all the cover
applies to any sport you attend as a spectator. Gold cover costs Pounds 124
a year for high risk, Pounds 84 for intermediate and Pounds 58 for low risk.
A discount of 20 per cent is available if you opt out of the weekly benefit.
Amsport also has separate policies for school-age footballers, as well as
adult football and rugby teams.
Wellesley (0279-626262) offers a policy for amateur sports teams of up to 20
people. The premiums are calculated by units and each covers each member of
the team for benefits of Pounds 5,000 each for death, loss of an eye or
limb, or permanent total disablement; Pounds 25 a week for temporary total
disablement; Pounds 10 a night in hospital; and up to Pounds 250 for dental
fees.
A cricket team would pay Pounds 125 a unit, a football team Pounds 165 and a
rugby team Pounds 450. Public liability cover of Pounds 1m is an optional
extra at Pounds 75 for a rugby team or Pounds 50 for other team.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
