<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / Finance and The Family: Directors' transactions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By COLIN ROGERS, The Inside Track
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE SHARE price performance of electronics group Vistec over the past 2 1/2
years has been strong. Robert Morton, the group's high-profile chairman,
capitalised when he bought 1.8m at between 10-13p in 1991. Now, chief
executive Adrian Wallis has sold 350,000 at 29p, having disposed of 650,000
for 26p at the start of the year.
Having slumbered peacefully for most of the past five years, Norbain
Electronics' share price burst into life at the turn of the year, rising
from a low of 58p to the present level, a record high. John Nicol, chairman
and managing director, has sold 350,000 shares at 155p. But perhaps this
disposal should be viewed in the context of two previous sales - one of 1m
shares at 37p, the other of 350,000 for the same price - in September 1991
and 1992 respectively.
There was selling this week in another electronics company, Logica. Logica
has had its fair share of problems in recent times but seems to have got
over the worst. In September 1990, Leonard Taylor, a non-executive director,
bought 100,000 shares at 155p and sold them for 236p a few months later.
This time, he and a colleague have each sold sold 75,000 at 245p, leaving
Taylor with about 1.4m.
