<DOCNO>FT933-12312</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DGYABADOFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930724
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / Finance and The Family: The Week Ahead
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
ON THURSDAY, Imperial Chemical Industries, the UK's largest chemical group,
reports its first interim results without its bioscience business, Zeneca.
Industry analysts' forecasts reckon pre-tax profits will be down from last
year's Pounds 159m (excluding exceptionals) to about Pounds 140m. Figures
will also be given for the old ICI, which included Zeneca. The performance
of the industrial chemicals division will also be watched closely. Its
titanium dioxide and caustic businesses are struggling, but chemicals and
polymers are expected to post significant improvements.
Zeneca also reports its half-year results on Thursday. Analysts expect it to
report pre-tax profits at between Pounds 330m and Pounds 340m. Of particular
interest will be the performance of the pharmaceuticals division.
Reuters, the international information and news group, is expected to report
an increase in interim pre-tax profits from Pounds 187m to about Pounds 210m
on Tuesday. Interest will centre on whether the group plans to distribute
some of its Pounds 710m cash pile to shareholders - and on the progress of
new dealing systems such as Globex, for financial futures and options
markets; and Dealing 2000-2, the automated foreign exchange product.
BAT Industries, the tobacco to insurance conglomerate, is expected to show
increased interim pre-tax profits on Wednesday. Despite concerns about the
prospects for the group's US tobacco business, profits are predicted to rise
to Pounds 710m-Pounds 780m (Pounds 672m a year earlier). Eagle Star, the
non-life insurance subsidiary, is gradually recovering profitability
following increases in premium rates and a fall-off in weather-related
claims.
The interim reporting season for clearing banks starts on Friday with
Lloyds, which is expected to show less of a rebound in profits than others
because of greater consistency in earnings in the past two years.
Lloyds is also expected to be under pressure in its net interest income
because its UK loan book has been contracting. But analysts expect it to
benefit from around Pounds 100m of release of less developed country debt.
Analysts expect a rise in pre-tax profit to Pounds 450m-Pounds 560m (Pounds
369m). Provisions for bad and doubtful debts are expected to fall to between
Pounds 250m and Pounds 270m from Pounds 347m.
British Telecommunications is reporting first-quarter results on Wednesday.
Pre-tax profits of about Pounds 780m (Pounds 731m) are likely.
</TEXT>
