<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / Finance and The Family: Ethical investment - honest, or just
hype? / The sector is small but has been growing steadily. Yet, some say it
is no more than a marketing tool
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HOW CLEAR is your conscience? Ever since the market in ethical and
environmental funds started to grow late in the 1980s, there has been a
suspicion that they are more a marketing tool than a wholehearted attempt to
offer investors the choice of putting money into companies meeting a series
of moral criteria.
The amount placed in these funds has been rising steadily, although it
remains a very small market. Some Pounds 365m was invested in
ethical/environmental unit trusts by May 1993 compared with Pounds 283m in
July 1991, according to the Ethical Investment Research Service (Eiris);
this monitors the activities of UK companies to see if they meet the
required criteria.
Most ethical/environmental funds are unit trusts but there is also a
smattering of investment trusts, such as Jupiter Tyndall Merlin's
International Green. Commercial Union runs an environmental pension fund,
while Henderson offers a Green personal equity plan and Homeowners, a
friendly society, has a Green Chip growth bond.
The type of fund you choose depends very much on your own views about a
given issue. Take Eagle Star's Environmental Opportunities fund, which might
seem a non-starter for many since the company is owned by BAT, the tobacco
group.
Eagle Star denies it is an ethical fund and says the trust 'should not in
any way be labelled a green trust; neither is it an ethical trust. We are
not making moral judgments.' Nevertheless, the company says its main aim is
to invest in 'far-sighted' companies which take a positive attitude to
environmental issues.
If you do not think tobacco is an environmental issue, this is not a
problem. But if you regard smoking as 'pollution,' you will not think of
this as a 'true' environmental fund.
Greener than White?
Idealists will find it difficult to find a perfect fund, partly because of
the different criteria chosen by the trusts. Some green funds will invest in
companies trying to clean up their act by using environmentally friendly
materials in their offices.
Others will invest in companies producing goods and services which
contribute to the environment, without taking a view on the shade of green
adopted by the management of the company.
John Allan, of Clerical Medical's Evergreen fund, says: 'We would avoid
investing in companies such as British Petroleum or Shell oil.
'But others will invest on the basis that these companies are involved in
research into the environment and are making efforts to clean up their act.'
A survey in this month's issue of Which?, the Consumer's Association
magazine, gives plenty of ground for disillusionment and would appear to
confirm the cynical view of ethical/environmental funds as marketing hype.
Its investigation, into 17 of them, found that none managed to avoid
completely five areas of ethical or environmental concern.
Only three of the funds - Ethical Investment, Friends Provident Stewardship
and Scottish Equitable - said they avoided companies where they were unable
to monitor investments.
The criteria chosen by Which? were animal testing, weapons, oppressive
regimes, political donations and green issues such as pollution, nuclear
power and ozone-depleting chemicals.
Some funds scored particularly low marks, although the criteria used did not
necessarily match the funds' own. TSB Environmental Investor rated the
lowest over animal exploitation because it invests in Unilever, which tests
cosmetics on animals.
Abtrust's ethical fund fared poorly in avoiding companies linked with making
or supplying arms because of an investment in Weir Group, the engineering
company which manufactures missile launching systems for nuclear submarines.
Abtrust, however, has sold its holding in Weir and says the company had been
under review for some time because of its activities.
The Environ trust run by Co-Operative Insurance (CIS) also fell short in the
survey. It has a holding in BOC, the industrial gases and drugs group which
has subsidiaries in countries such as China, condemned by Amnesty
International for human rights abuses.
Environ also has a stake in Siebe, an engineering company which makes parts
for nuclear submarines and has a subsidiary in South Africa which pays low
wages, according to Eiris.
Environ does avoid companies which, among other criteria, make more than 10
per cent of their turnover in countries with oppressive regimes, or in
arms-related activities. 'If you dig deep enough, you could find fault with
any company,' says David Mott, of CIS. 'We think we have been successful in
striking a balance between good investment returns and establishing criteria
which the average, caring investor would be happy with.'
Performance
CIS argues that it adopts a more relaxed policy than some funds in order to
assist performance, and this appears to be borne out by the table.
It was the second highest-performer of any ethical/green fund in the
international growth sector in the three years to July 1, although it has
not matched that performance in the year to July 1.
By contrast, Clerical Medical's Evergreen - which, along with Friends
Provident and Scottish Equitable's ethical fund, came out best in the Which?
survey - is second from bottom over the three years to July 1. It invests in
companies where a major part of the business lies in making a contribution
to the environment, but excludes those where other operations might cause
damage to the environment.
'This automatically means that we have a narrow band of companies which we
can invest in,' says Allan. 'Performance is affected to the same degree as
any fund limited to a narrow band, such as a single country emerging market
fund.'
Most of the companies involved in providing goods and services of the
environmental type tend to be small, so performance often can be volatile.
Ethical/green unit trusts underperformed the average for the two sectors
listed in the table in the year to July 1, but have outperformed the average
in the three and five years to the same date.
This should give cheer to idealists who also want good returns. 'Investors
should look around to find a fund that best meets their own principles,'
says Eiris.
'Some people may not find them perfect but, for many, one or more of these
funds will get them much closer to their ideal.'
And to a clearer conscience, Eiris could have added.
To celebrate its ninth anniversary, Friends Provident is offering an extra 1
per cent unit allocation for new investments of more than Pounds 3,000 into
Stewardship, the largest ethical fund.
The offer runs to September 17.
