<PROFILE>_AN-DGYABADFFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930724
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / Markets: Retailers - not a super market / The Bottom Line
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIR ALISTAIR Grant, chairman of Argyll, may be rereading his statement to
the group's annual meeting this week to find out just what he said to upset
the City so much. His statement, although generally positive, knocked 11p
off the share price of Argyll, which owns the Safeway superstore chain, and
precipitated another round of downgrades of analysts' profits forecasts for
the big food retailers.
There seems to be little anyone can do to lift the sector, which has
underperformed the stock market by more than 10 per cent since January.
The main fear is that intensifying competition and a growing price
sensitivity among consumers means the big grocery chains cannot sustain the
spectacular profit growth enjoyed in the last 10 years.
There are two elements to this. One is the fear that the UK food market is
approaching saturation, that there is room for only so many superstores
before they start 'cannibalising' each other's sales.
The second factor is the rapid spread of discount retailers, which cut costs
and margins to the minimum and concentrate on offering the lowest possible
prices.
The 'big three' grocery chains, Sainsbury, Tesco and Safeway, have played
down these threats. Only Archie Norman, chief executive of Asda, the UK's
number four, has broken ranks to warn that the 'halcyon days' of food
retailing are at an end.
Recently, a third threat has emerged: low inflation. While the government
has made strenuous efforts to reduce it, inflation is, in some ways, the
retailer's friend. Inflation means the value of a retailer's stock rises
between the time goods are bought and re-sold to the consumer, boosting the
profit margin. Low inflation means retailers have to be more efficient and
cut costs to maintain or increase margins.
Although Sir Alistair made some negative noises about 'highly competitive
trading conditions', inflation was the real reason the markets reacted badly
to his statement.
He said current inflation, at just under 1.5 per cent excluding petrol, was
'below our expectation of some modest food price inflation . . . The current
year is likely to be somewhat more challenging than anticipated a few weeks
ago.'
What is strange about the slide in share prices, is that it has affected
almost all the big food retailers, except for Asda, which is staging a
recovery after getting into financial difficulties at the end of the 1980s.
Analysts believe the sector will bounce eventually, but only those companies
who are perceived to have got their formula right will gain.
'It's true that it's dog eat dog in food retailing, but some of them are
rottweilers, and others are poodles,' says Bill Currie of BZW. 'The big dogs
will eat the little dogs.'
Sainsbury is agreed to be the rottweiler of the sector. Its shares are
recommended by most analysts. Some favour Argyll, but there are fears about
its spending on expansion. Tesco, however, is widely out of favour. It has a
younger customer base than its rivals, which has been hit harder by the
recession and is seen as more susceptible to the charms of the discounters.
Opinions differ on Asda. It is seen as a recovery stock, but many analysts
believe its price is already high enough.
Wm Morrison, the Bradford-based regional superstore operator which was voted
the UK's top-performing company by the Institute of Directors, has many
supporters in the City.
Among the discounters, Kwik Save, the oldest and biggest, is recommended by
some. But other analysts fear its decision to extend its range has left it
in 'no man's land', as neither a limited-range, deep discounter, nor a
discount superstore, and it may lose sales as a result.
Shoprite, the fast-expanding chain which operates mainly in Scotland, is the
only quoted deep discounter and some analysts believe it offers significant
growth potential.
But with few opportunities for good news before Tesco's interim results and
Asda's AGM in September, the sector may continue its downward drift for a
while. Those holding the stronger shares are not advised to sell, but for
those who do not, there is probably no rush to buy.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>J Sainsbury.
    Argyll Group.
    Tesco.
    Asda Group.
    Wm Morrison Supermarkets.
    Kwik Save Group.
    Shoprite Group.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P5411 Grocery Stores.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
