<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / Markets: Buffeted equities emerge unscathed again - Wall
Street
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ONCE AGAIN, the stock markets have been buffeted by the rapidly shifting
winds of corporate earnings, economic fundamentals, monetary policy and bond
price movements and, once again, they have emerged unscathed. The Dow Jones
Industrial Average even managed to set a record high during the week when it
closed at 3,555.40 on Wednesday. That achievement, however, was marred by
the failure of other indices to match its performance.
On the same day the Dow peaked, the Standard &amp; Poor's 500, the Nasdaq
composite and the American Stock Exchange composite all fell - an indication
that the buying which lifted the Dow into previously unexplored territory
was limited to a few leading stocks.
There was a further qualification to Wednesday's record-breaking gains: they
were achieved in the final minutes of business on the back of a series of
late computer program trades. And the fact that prices dropped sharply on
Thursday suggested that investors viewed the markets' breakthrough as an
opportunity to profits, not celebrate.
By midday yesterday, stocks were about back where they started the week.
Clearly, the equity markets remain trapped in a trading range between 3,450
and 3,550 on the Dow and, barring a big move from the Federal Reserve on
monetary policy or a dramatic shift in bond yields, they will probably stay
in that range for the rest of the summer.
The performance of corporate America appears unlikely to break the pattern,
although a cluster of surprisingly bullish second-quarter earnings' reports
were disclosed this week. There were strong showings from a wide variety of
industry groupings, including Sears, Roebuck (retailers); American and Delta
(airlines); Citicorp, Chase Manhattan, Salomon and Primerica (banks and
financial services groups); Texaco and Exxon (oil companies); Lockheed and
McDonnell Douglas (defence and aviation contractors; and SmithKline Beecham,
Schering-Plough and Merck (pharmaceuticals companies).
A large part of the quarterly reporting season is now out of the way,
although IBM has yet to announce its earnings. (This week, IBM shares
dropped to their lowest since 1975 as investors anticipated that the
computer group would announce further job cuts when it publishes its results
next week). For a couple of reasons, though, the latest batch of good
earnings news had little positive impact upon the markets as a whole.
First, the latest quarterly results represent snapshots of past performance.
Investors are much more interested in the future, and how well corporate
profits will hold up during what could be a sustained period of weak
economic growth. Second, with markets at or near record highs, many stocks
are looking expensive and strong earnings are priced into share values
already.
If corporate profitability is not greatly influencing equity markets, then
what is? The answer: interest rates and bond prices, the same factors that
have dominated stock market sentiment for the best part of a year. Share
prices are hovering around record highs because interest rates and bond
yields are hovering near record lows. Yet, share prices are struggling to
break from a narrow trading range and move any higher because many investors
fear that interest rates and bond yields may have bottomed.
These fears were not soothed by this week's comments from Alan Greenspan,
chairman of the Federal Reserve. In his semi-annual Humphrey Hawkins address
to Congress, he made a series of statements about inflation, the economic
outlook and interest rates that unsettled the bond market and further
rattled equity investors' already frazzled nerves.
There was nothing particularly new or shocking in what he said. He indicated
he was ready to raise interest rates at any time if warranted by inflation,
although he remained cautious about the inflation outlook in spite of
welcome improvements in recent consumer and producer price data.
In ordinary times, the bond and stock markets might have taken Greenspan's
remarks in their stride. But these are not ordinary times. Bond yields are
at record lows, share prices are near record highs, and investors are quick
to sell at the first hint of higher interest rates. There is little doubt
that rates will be raised sometime within the next six to 12 months. In an
accurate, but not particularly helpful, phrase, Greenspan said on Thursday
that a tightening of monetary policy was 'somewhere out there.'
The only question is: can corporate profitability and economic growth
improve sufficiently quickly so that, when a rate rise comes, the stock
markets will be strong enough to take it on the chin and stay upright?
Monday     3535.28 +  6.99
Tuesday    3544.78 +  9.50
Wednesday  3555.40 + 10.62
Thursday   3525.22 + 30.18
Friday     3546.74 + 21.52
