<DATE>930724
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / Markets: 'Advice' that you can do without - Serious Money
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNBIASED financial advice is hard to get. Unlike the legal, medical and
accountancy professions, where most people's worries are confined to whether
the adviser is clever or affordable, the financial services industry is
warped by a peculiar and intractable distortion - commission. It is
dominated by the large life offices which pay commission to salesman to sell
their products. The rationale is the old industry adage that people do not
buy insurance - they must be sold it.
Sale by commission is not confined to insurance products. It extends to
other investments such as unit trusts and even to deposit-based savings such
as some tax-exempt special savings accounts (when sold through an adviser).
There are two particular problems with the commission system. One is that
people do not know what proportion of their premiums is being used to pay
the commission - ie, they do not know the overall 'cost' of their
investment. The other is that payment by commission causes a potential
conflict of interest for the adviser, who might have to choose between
giving good advice and earning a living.
The Financial Services Act, which established the regulatory system, tried
to address some of the problems by dividing those who can sell products by
commission into two categories: the 'tied' agent, who can sell only the
policies of one company, and the independent financial adviser, who can
choose between products offered by the whole industry.
Tied agents must declare their affiliation before selling a product. This
will be familiar to many people who have taken out a mortgage in the past
five years, since almost all the large banks and building societies are tied
to a single life office.
There can be few people who would consult a doctor if they knew he was paid
by the drug companies to sell their medicine. He might be under pressure to
meet a sales target for a certain number of headache pills if he did not
want to be fired. This would hardly seem a desirable state of affairs.
Yet, the life offices are good at producing surveys showing consumers are
happy with the commission system. This is because many people do not
appreciate the way the system works.
Say, for instance, you want an endowment policy. Would you prefer to pay an
adviser to sell it to you or would you rather have the life company pay the
adviser?
Given that question, you might choose the latter. But, in fact, you end up
paying the adviser either way because the life company pays him out of your
premiums.
Although there are many hard-working and scrupulous commission-based
independent financial advisers, there are also many who are not, as the
plight of those misled into buying risky home income plans (see page IV) has
demonstrated amply. But the information gathered suggests that the greatest
problems have been caused by the tied agents and direct sales forces of the
life companies.
Anthony Nelson, economics secretary to the Treasury, who this week took an
important step to improve the system, said he had been alarmed by the high
lapse rates in the life industry - an indication as sure as any that people
are being sold policies they are either do not want or cannot afford. A
report by management consultant AKG showed that, in 1991, up to one quarter
of new life and pension policies lapsed within a year of their sale.
Policies sold by a direct sales force or a tied agent have the highest lapse
rates.
The action Nelson has taken is to order the regulators to draft rules
obliging both tied agents and IFAs to reveal the amount of commission they
receive when they recommend a product. He also wants companies to tell
consumers the effect the charges will have on their investment, by stating
the amount by which their investment is reduced as a result of the charges.
In ordering these and other changes, he has acted upon and extended the
scope of recommendations made by the Office of Fair Trading in March.
The industry is still drawing its breath before deciding what to do, but
most IFAs and life offices are not pleased. IFA Promotion, an association
representing the interests of IFAs, said yesterday: 'We are somewhat
disappointed that the chancellor sees commission disclosure as vital to the
consumer.'
Standard Life, one of the largest offices, has been blunter. 'The
chancellor's decisions are not what we were hoping for, especially in
relation to disclosure of commission and longer term surrender values,' said
spokesman Tom King. But the Consumers' Association is delighted.
The Treasury's action is certainly good news for the consumer, but the life
insurance industry has been adept at turning adverse circumstances to its
advantage. The danger is that the industry will adopt policies which will
succeed in frustrating the spirit of the Treasury's action when the new
rules are drawn up.
Finally, the measures still do not confront the central problem of providing
unbiased advice to those who seek it. Consumers can go to fee-based
advisers. This is a small market although it would expand were the
commission system eroded. Until this happens, consumers will have to
continue their hard search for unbiased financial advice.
</TEXT>
<XX>
