<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / Ex-Ferruzzi chief in apparent suicide
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MILAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR RAUL GARDINI, 60-year-old former chairman of Ferruzzi, Italy's second
biggest private sector company, was found in his Milan apartment yesterday
with a single shot to the head, an apparent suicide.
Mr Gardini was rushed to the first-aid unit of a nearby hospital, where he
was dead on arrival.
Magistrates were investigating Mr Gardini among others over alleged
corruption and illicit financing of political parties.
Yesterday afternoon an arrest warrant was issued for Mr Carlo Sama, the
former chief executive officer of Montedison, the controlling company of
Ferruzzi. Mr Sama is married to a daughter of the late Serafino Ferruzzi,
the company's founder.
Warrants were also issued for Mr Vittorio Giuliani Ricci, brother-in-law of
the late Mr Gardini, Mr Sergio Cusani, a close associate of Mr Gardini with
links to the Socialist party, and Mr Giuseppe Berlini, who manages the
Ferruzzi family finances.
Mr Sama was charged with falsifying the 1992 Montedison accounts which
reported an unexplained L320bn (Pounds 134m) extra loss after shareholders
had approved the balance sheet.
Mr Gardini's death was discovered just two hours before a funeral service
began in a nearby church for Mr Gabriele Cagliari, the former chairman of
the state-owned Eni energy and chemicals group. Mr Cagliari committed
suicide on Tuesday in his cell in Milan's San Vittore prison where he had
been held since March on corruption charges.
Mr Gardini and Mr Cagliari were rivals in the lengthy battle for control of
Enimont, the chemicals joint venture set up between Ferruzzi's Montedison
chemicals subsidiary and Eni in 1989.
Hailed as a long-overdue attempt to create a world-class Italian chemicals
group, management of the joint venture soon deteriorated into a lengthy war
of attrition between the two sides.
Magistrates investigating Enimont suspect that the events surrounding its
launch and its eventual dissolution in late 1990, when Eni bought out
Montedison's 40 per cent share, hide some of the worst excesses in Italy's
17-month-old political corruption scandal.
The Enimont affair may already have contributed to the suicide this year of
Mr Sergio Castellari, the top civil servant in the former Ministry of State
Shareholdings, closely involved in the formation and dissolution of the
joint venture. Mr Castel-lari's body was found on a hillside near his Rome
home.
Mr Gardini's death was almost certainly prompted by the return to Italy last
week of Mr Giuseppe Garofano, a former Montedison executive.
Mr Garofano, who went into hiding this year after being told by magistrates
he was under investigation over a L250m contribution to the Christian
Democrat party, was arrested in Geneva last week. He was apparently on his
way back to Italy to give himself up.
On Thursday night, an Italian news magazine released an extract of leaked
testimony from Mr Garofano, accusing Mr Gardini of various financial
irregularities at Montedison.
Mr Garofano reportedly confirmed suspicions that creating and dissolving
Enimont involved kickbacks to politicians and that Mr Gardini had authorised
property transactions to create a pool of L80bn-L100bn in off-balance-sheet
funds to pay kickbacks.
However, pressure had been mounting on Mr Gardini after his name was
formally added to those under investigation over Enimont earlier this year,
before Mr Garofano's return to Italy.
Obscurity to ignominy, Page 2
Scandalous saga, Page 9
</TEXT>
