<PROFILE>_AN-DGYABAC5FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930724
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / The Lex Column: ShareLink
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
ShareLink's over-subscribed flotation suggests private investors are still
eager to invest in new issues, especially those of smaller companies. Since
the returns on cash have dwindled and small company shares have risen
steadily - the FT-SE SmallCap index has roundly outperformed the FT-SE 100
this year - such enthusiasm is understandable. That is doubly good news for
ShareLink, which profits from individuals' willingness to buy and sell
shares. The question for both the company and the new issues market is
whether retail interest will evaporate at the first hint of a bear market.
The number of small shareholders has already fallen by almost 2m from the
11m peak reached in 1991, thanks in large part to recession. With few big
privatisation issues in the pipeline, there seems little to tempt the
first-time buyers out of alternative investments. Tougher disclosure rules
for life insurance might just help the cause of equities. But without
further tax incentives from government, the high ideal of a share owning
democracy will remain no more than that.
That will not bother ShareLink, though, so long as the remaining core of
private shareholders are prepared to trade. Its figures point to a hardened
band of investors dealing more regularly, in greater size, and  - one hopes
 -aware of the risks.
</TEXT>
