<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / The Lex Column: France
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The short term economic logic for floating the franc is increasing as
inexorably as the pressure on the foreign exchange markets. The surge in
French bond and share prices yesterday reflects the growing conviction that
interest rates will have to come down by one means or another. Paris
financial markets assume either that the Bundesbank will buckle next
Thursday and reduce rates - a seemingly unlikely prospect - or that a franc
float will enable France to cut the cost of borrowing.
Yesterday's increase in money market rates suggests the authorities are
determined to tough it out. The government has mobilised a panoply of market
tactics as well as the heavy artillery of intervention while the franc is
still more than a centime above its D-Mark floor. At present, there is a
solid political consensus behind the policy. There are no psychological
deadlines, such as elections or referendums, to force a resolution of the
issue. Though battered, the franc could remain in the fight for some time to
come.
Such a policy, though, would be unsustainable if it meant market interest
rates remained high and fed through into bank lending rates. With
unemployment nudging 12 per cent, the clamour for some economic stimulus
would grow shriller. The privatisation programme, which was finally
unleashed this week, would also be jeopardised. Domestic investors,
unsettled by job insecurity, would be loath to switch out of safe money
market funds. Overseas investors would be nervous about buying shares
denominated in a vulnerable currency. Both would worry about the dismal
outlook for corporate earnings.
</TEXT>
