<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / The Lex Column: Confidence factors
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
After Maastricht, Christchurch. By the end of next week Mr John Major will
at least have these distractions out of the way, but his leadership will
hardly have been strengthened by his recourse to a confidence vote on the
social chapter and what promises to be a crushing by-election defeat. If the
equity market has remained relatively sanguine, it may be partly because Mr
Major's desire to restore his credibility reinforces his need for a
growth-oriented economic policy.
Recent statistics, including yesterday's second quarter GDP figures, show
the recovery remains in place. Presumably Mr Major's hope is that after the
summer holidays, the shame of this month's reverses will have been forgotten
and the economic recovery will lend fresh vigour to his leadership. The
chances are that he will respond to any setbacks by cutting interest rates,
a thought which should continue to underpin equities.
But a sterner test looms in the form of the interim results season. While
higher gilt prices leave the gilt/equity yield ratio comfortably over two,
equity valuations look somewhat stretched by a market prospective multiple
in excess of 14. Since worries over insider trading have made companies
particularly reluctant to steer City forecasts, it is unusually difficult to
anticipate the message from interim results. The chances are, though, that
it could be one of mild disappointment. The UK recovery may not yet show
through strongly in earnings and the downturn in continental Europe has
accelerated. It would help UK companies if the current ERM unrest led to
lower continental interest rates which would boost demand.
</TEXT>
