<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / Pressures on House of Fraser shown in accounts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BOLGER and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STRASBOURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE FINANCIAL pressures which caused the Fayed brothers to announce plans to
float the House of Fraser department store chain next year became clearer
yesterday.
House of Fraser Ltd's net assets fell from Pounds 811m to Pounds 755m in the
year to January 30, the annual report showed. The store-chain subsidiary
includes 59 House of Fraser stores, and Harrods, which is not to be floated.
Even allowing for some adjustments, these figures mean the Fayeds would have
risked breaking covenants to House of Fraser's bankers, which required an
increase in net worth of 5 per cent a year.
The accounts also confirm that House of Fraser Ltd provided borrowing
guarantees to the group holding company amounting to Pounds 668m, of which
Pounds 616m had been drawn down at April 30. House of Fraser group denied
this week that the Fayeds were under financial pressure and said a
refinancing was arranged in April.
The accounts show that House of Fraser Ltd's borrowings were refinanced at
variable rates linked to the London interbank offered rate, but the terms
are not disclosed. One indication of financial pressure is that Pounds 60m
must be repaid by April next year and Pounds 175m before April 1995.
The Fayeds believe the flotation of the stores will enable them to reduce
their debts and to retain Harrods.
Turnover at House of Fraser Ltd grew by 4.6 per cent to Pounds 1.06bn in the
year to January, which the company described as a 'strong performance in
difficult market conditions'.
It said operating profits increased by 27 per cent to Pounds 74.5m. An
exceptional charge of Pounds 68.7m meant House of Fraser Ltd made a pre-tax
loss of Pounds 7.8m, compared with a profit of Pounds 40.3m the previous
year. The charge mainly related to the waiving of inter-company loans.
The European Commission of Human Rights said yesterday the Fayeds had not
been denied justice by Britain, Reuter reports from Strasbourg. The brothers
claim they were denied redress in British courts against a damning
Department of Trade and Industry report in 1990 about their business
affairs.
</TEXT>
