<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / London Stock Exchange: Pressure on life groups
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO, CHRISTINE BUCKLEY and ZHANG TINGTING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ORDER from the Treasury to securities regulators to draft rules
requiring life insurance agents to disclose more about their products took
the market by surprise and sent shares in the sector sharply downwards.
Dealers said the regulatory changes were 'more wide ranging than anybody had
anticipated' and were uncertain about how the life companies will cope with
them.
Among the big life companies, the biggest fall was recorded in Legal &amp;
General where the shares were down 33 at the day's worst before steadying to
close a net 31 off at 470p after hefty trading of 7.5m.
Also hit was Prudential Corporation, in which hectic trading brought heavy
volume of 20m as the shares fell 22 to 310p. Sentiment in Prudential was
already poor following the release of disappointing new business figures on
Thursday.
Goldman Sachs took both stocks off its buy list, downgrading them to a
'hold'. Mr Stephen Dias at the US investment bank said the new regulations
will cause uncertainty and put the whole sector under a cloud for some time.
But he predicted that stronger companies such as the Prudential would emerge
yet stronger in a slimmed-down life market. NatWest Securities urged
investors to buy Prudential saying that it offers the greatest upside on the
'orphan asset issue'.
The day's other casualties in the sector included Refuge Group which gave up
53 to 950p, United Friendly 'B' down 25 at 638p, and Lloyds Abbey which run
back 28 to 412p.
</TEXT>
