<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / Foreign Exchanges: French bid to scare speculators
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEPHANIE FLANDERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Bank of France took the initiative in the defence of the franc yesterday
when it raised the French 24 hour lending rate and joined the Bundesbank in
verbal and monetary support of the French currency, writes Stephanie
Flanders.
The French authorities announced the 2.25 per cent rate hike early in the
day, raising the official overnight rate to 10 per cent from the previous
level of 7.75 per cent. This was followed by a day of frequent and open
purchases of the franc by both the French and German central banks.
By the end of trading, a concerted official effort to keep the franc from
falling below Ffr3.418 against the D-Mark appeared to have worked. In
London, the French currency closed at Ffr3.416, a little stronger than
Thursday's close of Ffr3.419, but still little more than a centime above its
ERM floor of Ffr3.4305.
On balance, few in the market thought that there would be a realignment of
the ERM over the weekend, despite rumours of emergency EC monetary committee
sessions which were quickly denied. For many, the fact that the Bank of
France did not feel able to raise any other official rates showed that the
underlying cause of the crisis, too high real interest rates, remained.
'The market's mood is still very negative towards the ERM,' said Neil
MacKinnon of Citibank in London. 'The interest rate hikes that we've seen
this week from a number of countries are generally judged to be counter
productive and unsustainable against a background of deteriorating economic
conditions.'
Other recently embattled ERM currencies saw a similar easing of pressure.
The Spanish peseta closed at Pta79.63, a little up on Thursday's Pta79.84,
and the Portuguese escudo similarly held its own, closing at Esc99.85
against the D-Mark compared with the previous day's Esc100.25.
Less fortunate was the Danish krone, which lurched down towards its ERM
floor once again, closing at around Dkr3.8942 against the German currency
compared with a previous finish of Dkr3.8805. By the end of the week's
trading, the Danish currency had once again taken the French franc's place
at the bottom of the ERM currency grid, just above its floor rate against
the D-Mark of Dkr3.9016.
Meanwhile the yen strengthened, partly as a result of the European tensions.
The Japanese currency rose sharply across the board for much of the day, but
later retreated. It closed at Y159.75 against the pound, up from the
previous Y161.00, and nearly half a pfennig higher against the D-Mark at
Y62.11.
</TEXT>
