<PROFILE>_AN-DGYABACJFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930724
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / International Company News: Caterpillar does better than
expected
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CATERPILLAR, the world's biggest construction equipment maker, yesterday
unveiled better-than-expected second-quarter earnings, thanks to growth in
new business, record revenues and an improving economy.
In the three months to June 30, it earned Dollars 67m, or 66 cents a share.
A year earlier, the US recession and a bitter employee strike pushed the
company into the red with a loss of Dollars 64m, or 63 cents.
Sales and revenues rose 12 per cent to Dollars 2.91bn in the latest quarter
from Dollars 2.6bn, largely due to a 24 per cent rise in US sales, to
Dollars 1.44bn. Outside the US, sales edged 1 per cent higher to Dollars
1.37bn from Dollars 1.35bn.
Physical sales volume of machinery and engines rose 7 per cent. Higher
prices helped lift sales by 12 per cent, to Dollars 2.81bn, while pre-tax
profits climbed to Dollars 74m, against a loss of Dollars 100m a year
earlier.
The company said its overall earnings projections for the rest of the year
had not changed significantly. However it warned the outlook for Europe
continued to deteriorate in the second quarter. Caterpillar hopes higher US
sales will offset the shortfall.
Caterpillar's labour conditions remain uncertain. Although the United Auto
Workers' strike ended last April, the company has not resumed negotiations
with the union and a new contract has yet to be signed.
The company said its results would depend on the strength of the recovery in
the US, the severity of recession in Europe, and economic and political
conditions in Brazil, where the company has large operations.
Caterpillar's first-half profits were Dollars 101m, or Dollars 1, against a
restated loss of Dollars 221m a year earlier. Sales and revenues rose 17 per
cent to Dollars 5.6bn.
</TEXT>
