<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / International Company News: Gucci chief in fight to retain
50% shareholding - Court battle for control of luxury goods maker
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER and HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, MILAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A FIERCE battle for control of luxury goods maker Gucci is being launched in
the US courts and threatens to be as bloody as the family rivalries which
rocked the Italian fashion house for more than a decade.
Investcorp, the international investment bank based in Bahrain which owns 50
per cent of Gucci, is seeking to unseat the chairman and grandson of the
founder and win control of his 50 per cent stake through two court actions
begun in New York this week.
The bank claims that several operating subsidiaries of what was once one of
Italy's greatest fashion houses are 'in or near insolvency' due to the
conduct of Mr Maurizio Gucci.
Investcorp has won a temporary order freezing his 50 per cent stake for 10
days. The action was taken following Investcorp's claims that he was seeking
to put his holding out of the reach of the bank, which has rights of first
refusal over the shares.
Maurizio is the last remaining Gucci on the board and was the apparent
victor in a fight for control of the 70-year-old company which set fathers,
sons, brothers and cousins against one another in the 1980s.
Investcorp is also seeking to remove Mr Gucci through an arbitration
procedure alleging several violations of the shareholder agreement drawn up
in 1991, when Investcorp took its 47.8 per cent stake to 50 per cent.
Mr Gucci is alleged to have pledged shares to secure debts and borrowed
Dollars 800,000 (Pounds 533,000) from Gucci America without Investcorp's
knowledge.
Furthermore, Investcorp also alleges that in 1991 Mr Gucci planned to
auction 90 per cent of his stake to pay off a judgment against him.
Questioned on how he managed to repay the debt at the eleventh hour, without
selling his shares, Investcorp claims Mr Gucci said he had found the money
under the floorboards of his house after 'being visited in a dream by the
ghost of his father'.
A spokesman for Investcorp said the decision to resolve the dispute in court
followed two years of discussions with Mr Gucci over managing the company.
It is believed the bank has offered Mr Gucci the titular chairmanship as
long as it controls day-to-day running of the company. The bank is believed
to have identified a number of possible replacements for Mr Gucci.
Spokesmen for Mr Gucci in Milan dismissed the initiative. The arbitration
procedure 'can have no influence on the Gucci group shares, which are and
will remain Maurizio Gucci's', and the company would continue to be run
normally, they said.
Any conduct 'injurious' to the agreement between Mr Gucci and Investcorp 'is
solely attributable to the Arab shareholders', according to Gucci. As for
the criticisms of the group's management, these reflect a 'distorted reading
of the facts and strategies', which emerges in the 'divergent judgments
about the real situation of the Gucci group'.
The bank, which has come to prominence by purchasing, developing and selling
on western luxury goods companies such as Tiffany, Chaumet and most recently
Saks Fifth Avenue, claims Gucci has been deprived of vital funding.
Investcorp alleges that attempts to inject capital of between Dollars 50m
and Dollars 100m, in return for a controlling stake in Gucci, have been
rejected by Maurizio.
Gucci has had a troubled time since the bitter family dispute which
distracted managers' attention from running the business was finally
resolved in 1990.
Mr Gucci has tried to rationalise the group's products and geographical
expansion, both of which had grown out of hand in the booming 1980s.
The aim has been to return Gucci to its roots as a producer of up-market
accessories, notably shoes and bags, and clothing, rather than attach its
name to any articles which might sell.
The number of authorised sales outlets has also been pared, with a sharp
reduction in stores which are not deemed to be sufficiently upmarket or
suitably located to reflect the Gucci name. In addition, the product range
has been purged.
However, the restructuring has coincided with the severe recession in the
luxury goods market. Italian newspaper readers were astonished this month to
see discreet advertisements for an end of season sale at Gucci's flagship
stores in Milan's via Montenapoleone.
Sales are estimated to have fallen from more than Dollars 300m three years
ago to less than Dollars 180m, while a profit of Dollars 50m has been
reversed into a loss of more than Dollars 30m. Gucci is also reported to be
struggling with a serious liquidity problem.
Matters have not been helped by the increasingly strained relations between
Mr Gucci and Investcorp.
Late last year, strong rumours circulated that the company, or a significant
stake, was to be sold to the UK's Dunhill group.
The reports, swiftly denied, were immediately attributed by Mr Gucci's aides
to an ill-advised attempt by Investcorp to step up the pressure on the
family at an increasingly difficult time in the market.
</TEXT>
