<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / UK Company News: Hartstone secures agreement with lenders
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE FUTURE of Hartstone looked more secure yesterday after the hosiery and
leather goods group announced that it has reached agreement with its lenders
on a formal standstill arrangement pending a longer-term refinancing, writes
Paul Taylor.
The board also said it had reached agreement with its group of 14 lenders on
new facilities to cover the group's anticipated new money requirements until
the expiry of the standstill arrangement on January 16.
Hartstone's share price gained 7p to close at 56p yesterday.
The group stunned the City at the end of June by announcing Pounds 31m
above-the-line costs, to cover rationalisation charges, write-downs and
exceptional restructuring costs, and a Pounds 9.86m pre-tax loss for the
full year.
Hartstone announced at the time that it had breached banking covenants and
had begun refinancing talks with its bankers.
Yesterday Mr Shaun Dowling, executive chairman, said;'The signing of the
standstill arrangement and the provision of new money represent a
significant step in ensuring Hartstone's future.
The new money facilities include:
Cash advances and letters of credit facilities provided by the CIT
Group/Commercial Services under a new secured arrangement with Hartstone's
two principal US subsidiaries, Etienne Aigner and Michael Stevens, to
support their working capital requirements.
A FFr35m cash advance facility provided by the UK bank group through
Hartstone to Cogetex, the group's French hosiery company. In addition the
French bankers to Cogetex and Sotexa will provide a secured facility of
FFr50m backed by a guarantee of a similar amount from the UK bank group.
Overdraft and letter of credit facilities of Pounds 5.4m for Hartstone to
cover the requirements of its UK and Hong Kong businesses.
</TEXT>
