FT  24 JUL 93 / Letter: Danger of the soft option
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr BRIAN J MARCHANT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Over the last 10 to 15 years, like many of my colleagues I have had to
come to grips with zero defects, quality circles, Just-in-Time, 'The Lean
Machine', etc. Both as a manager and as a consultant I have tried to lead
companies down this path because I have seen the benefits it can bring, not
only in Japan. Needless to say, you must be prepared to invest a lot of hard
work and re-education at all levels.
Now I learn from your review of the Industrial Relations Services report
('Doubts over effectiveness of Japan-style work practices', July 19) that
all this was apparently in vain. As the recovery continues, 'pent-up
resentment from British workers . . . could have a devastating effect' and
'increase British industry's vulnerability'.
Are we really so stupid, as a nation, to throw away hard-won improvements by
taking the soft option? It would be interesting to hear the views of the
motor industry.
Brian J Marchant,
Marchants,
