<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / Letter: Trade associations are not mainly political
lobbyists
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From COL W T WILLIAMS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Andrew Taylor's article 'Lobbying not worth a button' (July 15) must
not be allowed to pass without comment. I am sorry my response is so delayed
but I have just returned from leading a trade mission to Tehran; very
successful, despite many problems on the way.
I must challenge the statement: 'The principal role of trade association is
to lobby government . . .'. This displays a degree of ignorance of the real
world that in itself casts doubts on whether the Department of Trade and
Industry lives on planet earth or elsewhere. The Engineering Industries
Association, a fairly substantial organisation with affiliates of some 2,000
small and medium-sized mechanical/electrical engineering companies, does not
see its main role as lobbying. Indeed, this is a fair way down its list of
priorities. The EIA is a 'one-stop shop'. We help our members with
legislative, commercial, financial or any other problems. We run
exhibitions; we sponsor overseas trade missions. We obtain trade
opportunities at home and overseas; we offer excellent courses/seminars at
low cost and we help with contractual problems.
When the government gets it wrong, as regrettably it all too frequently
does, then my members tell the secretary of state and will continue to do
so.
This dreadful old lobbying chestnut, as Lord Devlin's report demonstrates,
really ought to be buried.
We live in a parliamentary democracy. This means all voices must be heard.
The EIA's certainly will be. Convenience of ministers does not register very
far up the priority list. The secretary of state should listen to all voices
and decide on the course of action he wishes to pursue. He has more than
sufficient staff to help him.
W T Williams,
director-general,
Engineering Industries
Association,
16 Dartmouth Street,
Westminster,
London SW1H 9BL
