<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / Morbid twist to a scandalous saga: Victims of Italy's
crackdown
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Suicide has shrouded Italy's corruption scandals in the trappings of
classical tragedy.
The deaths this week, first of Gabriele Cagliari, the former chairman of
ENI, the state oil concern, and yesterday Raul Gardini, the leading Italian
financial entrepreneur of the 1980s, have injected a note of high drama into
the extraordinary process of change brought about by the 18-month judicial
investigations into illicit financing of political parties.
So far 10 persons under investigation have taken their lives. But Mr
Cagliari and Mr Gardini have touched a particular national nerve. Both were
captains of industry, one state, the other private-sector. They symbolised
the heady success of the 1980s and both had fallen from their pedestals.
Charges had yet to be pressed against Mr Gardini, but the investigative net
was closing in on him. Mr Cagliari had already admitted to knowing about at
least L50bn (Pounds 20.95m) worth of illicit funding channelled through ENI
and its subsidiaries to the Socialist and Christian Democrat parties.
The human tragedy, however, has not obscured the backdrop against which
these events occurred. 'The common thread behind these deaths is the
collapse of the conditions in which each of these personalities lived and
operated,' observed Mr Luciano Violante, head of the parliamentary
anti-Mafia commission.
It is a compelling thesis to see the suicides as the final stages of a
post-war political-economic system that has become hopelessly discredited.
Neither Mr Cagliari nor Mr Gardini could be called innocents. The
67-year-old former ENI chairman was both a servant of, and an accomplice in,
the system being ruthlessly exposed by magistrates. Over the past year, ENI
has emerged as the largest single source of illicit funding for the
political parties. For his part, Mr Gardini exploited the system and played
by its rules, even if this meant paying politicians in return for commercial
privilege.
Nevertheless the manner of the deaths induces pathos and sympathy. Mr
Cagliari killed himself with a plastic bag over his head, tied with a
shoelace, after being held for 133 days in prison. In a suicide note he said
he was protesting against the Milan magistrates' refusal to grant him bail.
Mr Gardini shot himself as yesterday's papers printed extracts of damning
testimony from Mr Giuseppe Garofano, his former management colleague at
Ferruzzi-Montedison, alleging fraudulent practices in Italy's second-largest
private group. Mr Gardini was alleged to have arranged up to L100bn in
political bribes, raised through off-balance sheet property deals, and
accused of illicitly covering a hole of more than Dollars 350m caused by
commodity trading losses. These accusations appeared in extracts released by
Il Mondo magazine which has consistently published reliable testimony from
interrogations in the scandals.
The immediate effect of the deaths has been to expose a growing division
between those who wish to halt the power of the magistrates - and by the
same token rein in the scope of their investigations - and those who want a
cathartic indictment of the political system that has ruled Italy since
1945.
In the first group are the bulk of businessmen and the politicians. This is
not surprising. Since one in six parliamentarians is under investigation for
corruption, they have a vested interest. The business community is genuinely
afraid that a concerted investigation of business methods risks invalidating
most company balance sheets.
This week, some politicians have tried to exploit Mr Cagliari's death to
confuse the issue between the magistrates' methods and the scope of their
inquiries. As a result, the magistrates will be obliged to use more
restrictively their considerable powers of preventive detention.
But the magistrates cannot be forced to halt their investigations without a
battle between the judiciary and the legislature. Significantly, Mr Cagliari
was the first top public-sector figure to be arrested, and his detention on
March 9 came immediately after a public outcry had forced President Oscar
Scalfaro to reject government proposals for an amnesty of those involved in
the corruption scandals.
The evidence this week suggests that despite public shock and personal
sympathy over the suicides, most people are firmly behind the magistrates.
The current parliament would enjoy little support for legislating an end to
the investigative process.
But pressure for such legislation might come from the many companies, state
and private, which have incurred losses through a combination of greater
international competition and recession. Mr Gardini's death will further
complicate the rescue of the Ferruzzi group, will affect four or five
leading financiers who were his associates, and will touch on the banks
which are exposed to Ferruzzi's L31,000bn debt.
Other big groups - Fiat, De Benedetti's Olivetti and Berlusconi's Fininvest
 -are caught up in the corruption scandals and risk damage from further
probes. The magistrates have yet to decide whether to tackle the
state-controlled banking sector - which would be the most sensitive
investigation of all.
</TEXT>
