<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / Lines of defence keep falling: Peter Norman examines the
latest troubles afflicting the franc in the crisis-prone ERM
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Crisis tends to be an overworked word in the European Monetary System.
But there is little doubt that the past week's turmoil, centred on a flight
from the French franc in Europe's semi-fixed exchange rate system, has
richly deserved the description.
Massive central bank intervention on Thursday - estimated at up to DM15bn
(Pounds 5.8bn) on the part of the Bundesbank alone - failed to give the
franc more than fleeting support in the European exchange rate mechanism.
By yesterday, the German and French authorities had resorted to their second
line of defence to keep the franc from falling to its Ffr3.4305 floor
against the D-mark. They produced a joint statement of support for the
franc's current EMS parity while the Bank of France pushed up its 24-hour
lending rate to 10 per cent from 7.75 per cent.
After a morning of more turmoil - made all the more confusing by the
backwash of the political crisis in Britain and signs of new trade tensions
between the US and Japan - it was difficult yesterday to find anybody
willing to say that the franc was out of the woods.
Europe's latest monetary troubles have shown the ERM at its worst. France is
in recession. As the graph shows, it is suffering from sharply rising
unemployment. Its inflation rate is low, with figures yesterday showing a
0.1 per cent drop in consumer prices in June and a year-on-year increase of
only 1.9 per cent. And yet the French authorities have been forced to push
their interest rates decisively above German levels when the nation needs
lower rates to cut unemployment.
Germany is also in recession. But unlike France it has an inflation problem.
Its money supply, up an annual 7.1 per cent in June, is growing faster than
the Bundesbank's 4.6 to 6.5 per cent target range. Regional cost of living
figures for July, due soon, are expected to show year-on-year inflation
accelerating from June's 4.2 per cent rate. And yet the Bundesbank is coming
under growing pressure from financial markets to cut its key discount rate
from 6.75 per cent by half or even a full percentage point.
The ERM's latest problems have not been confined to the French and German
currencies. The Danish krone has been subject to speculative pressures
similar to those suffered by the French franc, with the Danish authorities
forced to raise rates in its defence. Yesterday Belgium also tightened
credit conditions, with the Belgian national bank pushing its central rate
up to 7.15 per cent from 6.7 per cent and its emergency lending rate to 10
per cent from 8.5 per cent. Outside the ERM's 'hard core', both the Spanish
peseta and Portuguese escudo tumbled precipitately on Thursday as rumours of
an early ERM realignment swept the foreign exchange markets.
The crisis-prone nature of the ERM stands in marked contrast to its orginal
goal of creating 'a zone of monetary stability in Europe' when it was
launched in March 1979. Its present instability is causing a tightening of
monetary conditions in countries that are struggling either with slow growth
or recession. Since last September, when it was wracked by the crisis that
culminated in the departure of the British pound and Italian lira from the
system, the ERM has increasingly become an engine of speculation.
The disappearance of exchange controls in Europe and the ever-growing
interaction between the markets for foreign exchange, money, bonds and their
derivative products have given astute operators scope to move funds on a
massive scale from one market to another. They can speculate in the hope of
large gains from an ERM realignment or collapse of the system at the risk of
comparatively small losses. Central bank reserves offer only limited
protection against such forces and can be swiftly depleted. For example, in
the week to July 15 when speculation against the franc was modest compared
with week, the Bank of France's official net reserves fell Ffr17.81bn or
more than 10 per cent to an estimated Ffr137.16bn.
Some observers believe that the latest crisis facing the ERM could be bigger
than that of January and February, when the franc faced and withstood
speculative attack, and even the generalised ERM crisis of last September.
According to Mr Paul Chertkow, the London-based chief currency strategist of
UBS, the Swiss banking group, it is ominous that the speculative pressure in
the system has grown without any political event, such as last September's
French referendum on Maastricht, acting as a catalyst.
The pressure on the ERM may yet grow in intensity because some of the big
players of last September have yet to join the fray. Although there were
reports late this week that conservative pension funds were pulling out of
the French bond market and moving into German government paper, there has
been no sign yet of a decisive attack on the weak ERM currencies by the New
York-based hedge funds, which last autumn toppled sterling.
At the same time, however, France's ability to withstand speculative selling
of the franc through higher interest rates has declined. In earlier crises,
France's banking system could protect clients from the worst effects of the
higher interest rates. It is thought that this is less true today, after
recession and a depressed property market have cut into the banks' capital.
So far, the consensus in France, Denmark, the Netherlands and Belgium has
been strongly in favour of the EMS. But business people on the continent are
becoming aware that there is an alternative.
Britain's recovery since leaving the ERM was highlighted yesterday by gross
domestic product figures showing growth of 0.5 per cent between the first
and second quarters of this year. Over the past fortnight, the UK has
reported the strongest monthly increase in manufacturing output for four
years, a fifth successive monthly fall in unemployment, robust retail sales
growth and the fastest growth in manufacturing productivity in more than six
years. Inflation in the UK has remained subdued. Indeed, despite
devaluation, unit wage costs in UK manufacturing have just recorded their
largest fall since records began in 1970 and are falling faster than in any
other member of the Group of Seven leading industrial countries.
While economic logic might point increasingly in the direction of a
departure of the franc from the ERM, political considerations point the
other way. Mr Edouard Balladur, has threatened to resign if the franc is
devalued. The franc fort remains crucial to the government's policy of
binding Germany into a more integrated Europe and pressing ahead towards the
the Maastricht treaty goals of economic and monetary union.
And there is, indeed, a rosy scenario in which the foreign exchange market
travails of the past weeks would quickly be forgotten. If the Bundesbank can
be persuaded to ease its credit policy, France and the other embattled ERM
members should be able to lower their rates and return to growth, building
on their success in reducing inflation.
In some respects the scenario is not so far fetched. Figures this week
showed that French manufacturing output rose 0.2 per cent in May while
Insee, France's official statistics organisation, has forecast stable GDP in
the third quarter and a small gain towards the end of the year.
However, the Bundesbank seems unlikely to oblige with a rate cut soon
enough. Its decision-making central council meets for the last time before
its summer break next Thursday. Yesterday, Mr Reimut Jochimsen, one of
Germany's regional central bankers who is also a council member, said a cut
in German interest rates was 'not on the cards' because of high inflation
and excessive government borrowing. Analysts agree that financial markets
will keep the ERM under strain in the absence of a German rate cut. The
longer the pressure keeps up, the more likely the system is to buckle.
The traditional response to such acute crisis in the ERM has been
realignment of currency parities. But political conditions in France make
this especially difficult.
Restoring exchange controls is a theoretical possibility but is extremely
unlikely because of practical problems and the huge damage that it would
inflict on the EC's internal market.
On Thursday, rumours swept the market that the EC would decide wider
fluctuation margins than the current 2.25 per cent either side of bilateral
central rates for the D-mark, French franc, Danish krone, Dutch guilder,
Belgian franc and Irish punt. They could be widened to the 6 per cent
margins used by the Spanish peseta and the Portuguese escudo or further. But
such a move would represent a profound setback for the system and might
prove no more than a short-term palliative if the weak currencies were
pushed quickly to their new limits.
If pressure intensifies, market analysts in London believe that there may be
no alternative but to suspend the system until economic conditions in France
and Germany come more into line.
Such an action would be drastic and there is no sign of politicial support
for such an idea on either side of the Rhine. But the EMS since German union
at the end of the 1980s has been hallmarked by the failure of the system's
political masters to react in time to events. Developments this week suggest
that, in this respect, nothing has changed.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>FRZ  France, EC.
    DEZ  Germany, EC.
</CN>
