<DATE>930724
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / Leading Article: Mr Major's last gambit
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
IN THE END the power of a prime minister is the power of dissolution. By
making the Tory rebels choose between the Maastricht treaty and the likely
extinction not just of the government, but perhaps of their party, Mr Major
has played for the highest possible stakes and won. Some argue, wrongly,
that this will prove a Pyrrhic victory. True, it has been costly, but it is
still far better than a defeat. Yesterday's vote keeps the UK where it
should be, inside the European Community.
Mr Major has made many mistakes: mistakes over the ERM, over the economy,
over political management and over this treaty. For all that, he was right
on the essential point. The UK has no future isolated from the powerful
economies to its east. Naturally, it has its own traditions, interests and
ideas, which are often difficult to reconcile with those of its closest
neighbours. But the UK is either in Europe or in limbo. Mr Major understands
this. To his credit, he obtained a treaty his party could just about live
with and will now be able to ratify what he obtained. His tactics may often
have been inept, but the strategy has been correct.
The extent of the difficulties the prime minister has faced must also be
acknowledged. There is a majority in parliament, however unenthusiastic a
majority, for ratification of the treaty. But, as became obvious on
Thursday, offered a choice between a treaty without the social chapter and
one with it, many Tories who hoped for no treaty at all would vote for the
latter option, so depriving the government of its majority.
Steep price
By turning the question into one of confidence, Mr Major took this option
away from the rebels. But the political price he has had to pay is a steep
one. Many in his party are embittered by what the prime minister has done,
although he will be encouraged that none pushed rebellion to the point of
losing the whip and so further reducing his majority. That majority and Mr
Major's authority are likely to be further diminished by the Christchurch
bye-election. More damage may yet be done by whatever emerges about his
discussions with the official Unionists. But at least Mr Major can now focus
public attention upon matters other than the tortuous tedium of Maastricht.
He can also enjoy the fact that he has come out of this battle better than
has Mr Smith, a man who has seemed willing to play fast and loose with his
Euro-enthusiast principles. Mr Major may not be a brilliant politician. But
he has at least proved a dogged one.
The Maastricht treaty is now ratified in the UK, unless, as is most
improbable, Lord Rees Mogg's suit against it succeeds. The only remaining
obstacle is then the German constitutional court. In all probability, the
European Union will soon be born. What might that mean, not just for the EC
but also for the UK?
Not for many years has the likely future development of the EC been more
obscure: the Maastricht treaty has been ratified, but with great difficulty;
the ERM, the foundation stone of economic and monetary union, is shaking
once again; the parity of the French franc against the D-Mark is under
pressure; economic and monetary union looks no more than a distant hope; the
European economy is in recession; unemployment appears an intractable threat
to social stability; and, last but not least, dreams of foreign policy
co-operation are daily belied by the carnage in Bosnia.
Immensely risky
Faced with this crisis, the central players, Germany and France, may embark
on a determined move towards greater integration. Such a response would be
far from unprecedented. But it would be an immensely risky course, since it
might well fail to win support even in those countries. It would certainly
shatter any hopes for peace in the Tory party. It might also disrupt the
Labour party. For the moment at least, Maastricht seems as far as the UK is
able to go. It is certainly as far as the Conservative party can go.
Alternatively, scarred by recent failures, continental politicians may
concede the wisdom of a different agenda, one based on enlargement and
economic deregulation. If so, the UK would be able to play a more central
role than hitherto. It need not be in a permanent minority of one, but may
be able to be a helpful participant in the reformulation of Europe's future.
But that development, however helpful to the Conservatives, would be
disturbing to the Labour party, which has come to embrace the EC largely
because of its social programme.
Nobody knows how the game will now be played, either in the EC or in the UK.
The divisions inside British political parties are at least as deep as over
any previous issue. But this is hardly surprising, since the question of
Europe determines the kind of polity in which the political game is played.
The issue of Europe could still shatter British politics. But it need not
come to that. Much will depend on where Europe goes. A British prime
minister cannot determine the rules of the European game. But Mr Major has
at least kept the UK as a player. For that, he deserves credit.
</TEXT>
