<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / Holiday executives charged with fraud
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER, Leisure Industries Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TWO SENIOR executives of the Land Travel coach company, which collapsed a
year ago, have been charged with fraudulent trading, Avon and Somerset
Police said yesterday.
Mr Valere Tjolle, who was chairman of the Bath-based company, and Mrs
Theresa McDermott, who was company secretary, are to appear before Bath
magistrates on August 25. The police, who have been investigating the
company since its collapse in July last year, said the two were charged this
week after a fraud squad interview.
An estimated 40,000 holidaymakers were believed to have lost their money in
the collapse. Land Travel was not a member of the Association of British
Travel Agents and had not arranged a bond to protect customers' money.
Mr Tjolle bought the company from the Granada Group in 1990. At the time of
its collapse the company was offering three-day coach holidays in Paris or
Brussels for Pounds 49 and 10 days in Poland for Pounds 159. In the years
that Mr Tjolle owned the company it made heavy losses. In 1990-91 losses
were Pounds 1.8m and in 1991-92 they were Pounds 2.7m.
Land Travel's case led to warnings by the industry that further failures
were likely. European Community rules which came into effect at the start of
the year were aimed at ensuring that customers would not lose their money in
the event of collapse. Package travel companies now have to arrange bonding
or insurance on customers' behalf.
The effectiveness of the new regulations was put in doubt by the collapse
last May of SFV Holidays, a small Oxford-based company which was unbonded.
It emerged that Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, had told
the company that it did not need bonding because it allowed customers to
specify which ferry service they wished to use.
</TEXT>
