<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / Parliament and Politics: Sailor faces a lashing from whip
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IT IS PERHAPS appropriate that Mr Rupert Allason lists 'sailing close to the
wind' as his only Who's Who recreation. The Conservative MP for Torbay
appears to have been doing just that by being absent from yesterday's
Commons votes.
Mr Allason may find himself in hot water both with the government whips and
his constituency association as a result of his failure to appear.
One Tory loyalist said scathingly that the 'honourable member for Bermuda
North' had been summoned to see Mr Richard Ryder, the chief whip, on his
return. The remark reflected the widespread assumption that Mr Allason was
away in Bermuda.
The MP for Torbay since June 1987 now faces the threat of having the
Conservative whip withdrawn - which would isolate him from party activities
at Westminster and bar him from standing as an official Tory candidate at
the next general election.
In a statement released last night Mr Allason said: 'The dilemma I faced was
whether to keep the promise I made last year, not to assist in the passage
of the Maastricht treaty, or whether to back an administration that has
declared its intention to ignore the will of the Commons.
'It is quite clear from last night's vote the Maastricht Bill has been put
into limbo and the social chapter issue given the last rites. To insist on
pursuing ratification of the treaty is, in my judgment, absolute folly and
that is how I believe history will judge the issue.'
Squadron-leader Johnny Johnson, chairman of Mr Allason's constituency
association, said his MP's absence was 'curious, disappointing and as far as
I am concerned anger-making'. He had tried to call Mr Allason in London
before being passed information implying that he was 'in his Bermuda home'.
He said Mr Allason was neither popular nor unpopular with the association.
It was 'unlikely at this time' that moves might be taken to deselect him
'for political reasons'.
Mr Allason held Torbay at the last general election with a majority of 5,787
over the Liberal Democrats.
No Maastricht enthusiast, Mr Allason frequently decided against voting in
accordance with whips' instructions during the tortuous committee stage. He
is arguably better known to the public at large as the spy-writer Nigel
West.
</TEXT>
