<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / Parliament and Politics: Sideshow waits patiently for its
moment in the spotlight - David Butler samples the mood and opinions of the
people of Christchurch, the next jury to judge the prime minister
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUTLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CHRISTCHURCH knew yesterday that it was only a sideshow to Westminster.
But it showed, in its own quiet way, the national relief at the end - if it
is the end - of the Maastricht saga. Indifference rather than excitement
marked most reactions.
The politically active were, of course, entranced by Thursday night's drama
and yesterday's votes, but chance encounters revealed boredom and
disillusion.
'I don't know where Maastricht is,' complained a housewife. 'It's not
Europe, it's pensions that worries me,' said an oldster. 'I can't stand
these silly games in parliament,' was the barman's comment.
The parties in Christchurch tried to campaign seriously. Each brought in a
big gun. Virginia Bottomley came to support the Conservative candidate
Robert Hayward. She and he agreed, unconvincingly, that all was well and
that, once yesterday's business was out of the way, the electorate would
face the real issues and stay with their traditional Tory loyalty. Mrs
Bottomley tried vainly to persuade journalists, whose eyes were on the
parliamentary drama, that health care in Dorset was especially excellent.
Gordon Brown dutifully came to support Labour's hopeless campaign.
Thursday's events, especially the 'bribing' of the Ulster Unionists and the
wooing of Nicholas Winterton, provided a useful text. But even Mr Brown's
eloquence may not be enough to prevent Labour's 12 per cent vote in 1992
from being squeezed into a lost deposit.
For the Liberal Democrats Alex Carlile troubled the local party by
predicting a landslide. He had forgotten the new campaigning wisdom -
'always understate your expectations'.
But plainly everything in this, the 13th-safest Conservative seat, is going
the way of the Liberal Democrats. They have far more posters in front
gardens and far more helpers in the committee rooms and on the doorsteps.
Although they have had to build their organisation from scratch the result
is impressive and in Diana Maddock they have an adequate standard-bearer.
Christchurch is the epitome of a comfortable Tory seat with pleasant villas
and busy shops and a New Forest fringe. An afternoon canvassing with Robert
Hayward revealed a multitude of unopened doors as well as a handful of Tory
loyalists, a few civilised 'don't knows' and one Labour activist.
Mrs Maddock was making a significant haul of Tory and Labour deserters
willing to go public about their defection. A TV producer noted that Mr
Hayward had become reluctant to be filmed canvassing because the doorstep
reactions too often proved embarrassing.
It seems that the landslide threatening the Conservatives in Christchurch
owes little to Maastricht - but much to domestic issues and the sense of
government disarray.
Mr Major may have transformed the national situation by his well-whipped
success in the Commons yesterday persuading his rebels not to vote for an
early election. But, granted the phlegmatic, even indifferent attitudes
evidenced in Christchurch, it does not seem that yesterday's outcome in
Westminster will greatly affect the prospects for Thursday's by-election.
David Butler is a Fellow of Nuffield College, Oxford.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
