FT  24 JUL 93 / Rescue agreed for French benefits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE French government, employers and unions yesterday agreed a FFr25bn
(Pounds 2.84bn) a year rescue over the next decade for the country's
unemployment compensation system, writes David Buchan in Paris.
Mr Michel Giraud, labour minister, said the deal, which will see a FFr4.6bn
a year cut in unemployment benefits 'settles the future' of the system,
which recession has pushed into a deficit of more than FFr30bn.
Under the terms of the rescue package, the state is for the first time
making a sizeable contribution to the fund by providing an extra FFr10bn a
year. Hitherto, the scheme has been largely financed by employer/employee
contributions, which will be increased under the terms of yesterday's deal.
