<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / Reform moves put squeeze on LDP
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT THOMSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
JAPAN'S leading opposition parties yesterday moved closer to forcing the
Liberal Democratic party out of office by agreeing to political reform
proposals that would be the policy priority of a seven-party coalition
government.
The parties have yet to agree on the fine details of the co-operation but
generally accepted the introduction of one-seat constituencies and
proportional representation to replace the present scandal-prone, multi-seat
constituency system.
Mr Morihiro Hosokawa, leader of the Japan New party, proposed the new system
in tandem with the New Harbinger party, but also indicated that a coalition
government would need a coherent economic policy to deal with the present
downturn.
Four other parties  - Komeito, the Japan Renewal party, the Democratic
Socialist party, and the United Social Democratic party  - supported the
proposal, while the Social Democratic party, the largest opposition party,
agreed, but needs formal approval from officials next week.
The parties must also agree on a candidate for prime minister, as a vote
will be taken during an extraordinary session of parliament early next
month. It appears that either Mr Hosokawa or Mr Tsutomu Hata, the JRP
leader, will be chosen as the representative, but the SDP, hit by a bitter
internal struggle, could still bring the coalition undone.
LDP officials plan to choose a prime ministerial candidate next Friday, but
the agreement among the opposition parties yesterday will make it more
difficult for the LDP to find a partner to ensure success in the
parliamentary vote.
The LDP won 223 seats in last Sunday's election, while the seven opposition
parties collected 243 and expect support from independents in the 511-seat
lower house. However, if the SDP pulled out, the coalition would have only
173 certain votes, and the LDP candidate would win.
Japan's need for political reform was highlighted again yesterday when
public prosecutors arrested another provincial governor suspected of
allegedly receiving Y30m (Pounds 186,000) in illegal donations from
construction companies.
</TEXT>
