<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / Talks on Nafta side-agreements
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TRADE ministers from the US, Canada and Mexico will meet in Washington next
week to take final decisions on environmental and labour pacts to be
attached to the North American free trade agreement. Canada's chief
negotiator, Mr John Weekes, reported 'considerable progress' yesterday after
a week-long meeting of officials from the three countries in Ottawa.
A consolidated text with some remaining areas of disagreement is expected to
be submitted to the ministerial meeting, which starts on Thursday.
Nafta is due to be implemented on January 1, but the Clinton administration
in the US has said the pact will not be submitted to Congress until the two
side-agreements are finalised.
The prospects of Nafta being put into force as scheduled have brightened
markedly in recent weeks. The US administration is anxious to submit the
entire package to Congress before the recess which starts on August 6.
The administration is confident that congressional approval can proceed
despite a legal wrangle over whether a full assessment is required of
Nafta's environmental impact. A US court last month ruled that such an
assessment is necessary, but the Justice Department has appealed against the
ruling.
Mr Weekes said that enforcement of the proposed environmental pact remained
an issue, in particular Washington's demand for trade sanctions against
offenders.
Canada and Mexico consider the US demands to be an infringement on their
sovereignty, and are concerned at the risk that environmental disputes may
spur trade protectionism.
Mr Weekes declined to predict the outcome of next week's meeting. But he
said the negotiators tried to do some 'creative thinking' to facilitate the
task of the ministers.
Among the proposals floated recently has been a North American Environmental
Fund, which would finance anti-pollution projects and clean-ups, especially
along the US-Mexico border.
</TEXT>
