<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / Hyundai Motor compromise on pay accepted
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN BURTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SEOUL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
WORKERS at Hyundai Motor yesterday approved, by a slim margin, a compromise
wage agreement that is likely to end action that has disrupted South Korea's
largest industrial group for 50 days.
Hyundai Motor is the largest of nine Hyundai companies that have been on
strike since early June. The other companies are expected to end their
disputes next week.
The wage pact followed an 11th-hour agreement reached after the government
ordered workers to suspend their strike and threatened to impose a
settlement.
The government has been angered by the long strike, which has caused almost
Dollars 300m (Pounds 200m) in lost exports and Dollars 1.25bn in lost
production, when most other companies' workers have agreed to accept
moderate pay increases this year as part a programme to revitalise the
ailing economy.
The lukewarm response to the Hyundai Motor agreement, which was approved by
a bare majority of 50.09 per cent of the company's 29,500 workers, reflected
dissatisfaction that many of their demands were not achieved.
The Hyundai Motor workers, who are among the highest paid in South Korea,
were forced to accept the company's pay offer of a 4.7 per cent increase
instead of the 16.5 per cent they sought. In exchange, they received
increased fringe benefits, including longer holidays and housing subsidies
and other allowances.
The workers were also forced to drop proposals to increase their bargaining
position, including the introduction of a union shop and a greater say in
management and hiring policies though the Hyundai trade unions are among the
most militant in the country.  The government has also blamed Hyundai's
'authoritarian' management style for the persistent labour problems
affecting the group.
Mr Chun Song-won, president of Hyundai Motor, said he would try to improve
management-labour relations, as a result of the dispute.
The remaining Hyundai companies engaged in industrial action include Hyundai
Heavy Industries, Hyundai Precision &amp; Industry, Hyundai Mipo Dockyard,
Hyundai Electrical Engineering, Hyundai Wood Industries, Hyundai Pipe,
Hyundai Construction Equipment and Korea Flange.
</TEXT>
