<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / Nomination hearing delayed by Republicans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
US REPUBLICANS yesterday succeeded in delaying the Senate confirmation
hearing of Dr Joycelyn Elders, President Bill Clinton's nominee for
surgeon-general, who is under fire for her strong advocacy of birth control
help for teenagers.
Dr Elders had just finished her opening statement detailing her rise from
poverty to director of the Arkansas Health Department when Senator Don
Nickles, an Oklahoma Republican, demanded the hearing be postponed. Under
Senate rules, any member can delay a hearing being held more than two hours
after the regular Senate session begins.
The nominee, a formidable black woman, has been targeted for attack on
several grounds: her strong support of sex education, her outspoken support
for abortion, and financial and ethical dealings in both her professional
and private life. The White House is standing firmly behind the nomination
after being criticised for having caved in too quickly to attack on other
nominations - particularly that of Ms Lani Guinier, another black woman,
named to the Justice Department.
Senators were expected to question her about a negligence suit against her
and other board members of the National Bank of Arkansas, which was
ultimately settled. There may be trouble about her husband's failure to pay
social security taxes for a nurse taking care of his elderly mother, and she
will be questioned about drawing a full-time Arkansas state salary while
working part-time for the federal government, during her transition to the
surgeon-general's job.
Meanwhile, another Clinton nominee, Mrs Ruth Bader Ginsburg, seemed on her
way to winning confirmation to the Supreme Court after enduring and mostly
parrying intense questioning for three days.
</TEXT>
