<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / Obscurity to ignominy in a decade: The rise and fall of
buccaneering entrepreneur Raul Gardini
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Raul Gardini will be remembered as emblematic of an era in Italian family
capitalism.
From the mid-1980s, he built up the Ferruzzi group from a highly profitable,
but limited, farm products and trading organisation into the country's
second biggest private sector company. In less than a decade, the previously
obscure Ferruzzi family, into which Mr Gardini married, became as familiar
to Italians as the Agnellis, Pirellis and other leading families of private
sector business.
Mr Gardini, dubbed 'Sir Raul' or 'the pirate' by the Italian press for his
swashbuckling business style, defied the financial establishment through a
string of daring takeovers, culminating in the 1986 acquisition of the
Montedison chemicals group.
By daring to seize Montedison, which had see-sawed between private and
public-sector control in the previous two decades, Mr Gardini cocked a snook
at both politicians who had grown accustomed to using the chemicals sector
as an important source of patronage, and Mediobanca, the powerful Milanese
merchant bank and Montedison shareholder.
Mr Gardini, 60, was born into a property-owning family from Ravenna on
Italy's northern Adriatic coast. In spite of his middle class roots, he was
a far cry from the normal members of the salotto buono - the good drawing
room of northern Italian capitalism from which Mediobanca traditionally drew
its support and which it liberally financed.
Mr Gardini's courage and breadth of vision often allowed him to succeed in
transactions from which more sober counterparts would have shied away. The
Montedison coup was followed by string of deals which took Ferruzzi into new
businesses ranging from pharmaceuticals to building materials and energy.
The group also expanded abroad, making Mr Gardini's face as familiar to
French, UK or US investors as that of Fiat's Mr Gianni Agnelli or Olivetti's
Mr Carlo De Benedetti.
Mr Gardini's rise was a reflection of the boom in Italy's equity markets in
the mid-1980s, when share prices surged and the prestige of financial
engineers rose high above their mechanical counterparts, on which so much of
Italy's wealth depends.
His success in mounting takeovers and asset stripping were partly helped by
the absence of rules, which have since been passed, governing compulsory
takeover bids and forbidding the sales of majority or large stakes in
companies at a premium.
Such business ethics did little to endear Mr Gardini to international
investors when transplanted abroad. Ferruzzi aroused suspicions in the City
of London for poor transparency and a cavalier approach in its attempted
takeover of British Sugar.
Mr Gardini's domineering business style, based on his forceful personality,
was buttressed by his wife's stake in the Serafino Ferruzzi family holding
company. After the founder died in a 1979 air crash and his son, Arturo,
showed a clear preference for the sidelines, the field was virtually clear
for Mr Gardini. Ferruzzi and Montedison became virtually a one man empire,
with Mr Gardini largely unhindered by independent-minded managers or
demanding outside shareholders, whose insight into the group was complicated
by the group's complex 'cascade' structure.
In some cases, that permitted decisiveness and fast decision-making which
left visiting bankers breathless. But in others, the concentration of power
led to excesses, such as Montedison's multi-million dollar challenge for the
Americas Cup yacht race or the brief appointment of Mr Gardini's young son
Ivan as chairman of Ferfin.
In the end, Mr Gardini's ambition and the lack of control led to his
downfall. Upset by the reluctance of other members of the Ferruzzi family to
back his plans to buy out the state's stake in the Enimont chemicals joint
venture, the final break with the Ferruzzis came when the family rebelled
against his plan to reorganise the family holding company to guarantee the
predominance of the Gardini branch.
Mr Gardini negotiated a L505bn (Pounds 211m) pay-off for his wife's share in
the family company, and used the funds as seed capital to set up a new
business empire. His death removes one of Italy's most exciting, if
mercurial businessmen, and eliminates one of the central players able to
shed light on the tormented affairs of Ferruzzi and its affiliates at a
crucial time in their history.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Ferruzzi Finanziaria.
</CO>
<XX>
