<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / Energy contract accepted by eastern Germany
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BERLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE partial privatisation of east Germany's electricity sector has been
brought a step nearer following the removal of the last remaining obstacle
to the Stromvertrag, or energy contract.
Boizenberg, a small town in the eastern state of Mecklenburg-Vorpommern, has
decided to accept the Stromvertrag, signed in August 1990 between the then
two German states. It was the last of 164 local councils to hold out against
implementation.
The agreement ends a two-year-old battle by eastern councils to challenge
the contract, which in effect creates an energy monopoly in the five new
states. The acceptance of the Stromvertrag by eastern Germany's
municipalities will allow the Treuhand, the agency charged with privatising
east German industry, to press ahead with the partial privatisation of the
region's 15 regional utilities. But the Treuhand's ability to use
privatisation to introduce more competition in eastern Germany's electricity
sector is restricted by the contract.
The Stromvertrag allows local councils to own 49 per cent of all eastern
Germany's regional utilities. The remaining 51 per cent is divided between
western Germany's eight utilities, which are currently negotiating the
purchase of that stake from the Treuhand.
The Stromvertrag also gave western Germany's eight utilities a 100 per cent
stake in Veag, east Germany's high voltage grid. Veag will be privatised by
the Treuhand later this year. The eight western utility companies have
insisted that the east's regional utilities must buy 70 per cent of their
power from Veag over the next 20 years in order to cover the large
investments. They are only free to generate 30 per cent of their local
energy needs.
Several councils challenged the monopolistic implications of the
Stromvertrag. Constitutionally, they argued they had a right to a full 100
per cent access to the assets of the regional utilities - or else
compensation - because they owned them until they were expropriated by the
east German communist state in 1952.
The compromise allows the councils to sell their 49 per cent stake in the
regional utilities in return for access to their assets. Other cities, and
then the eight west German utilities will have first option to obtain the
shares.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>DEZ  Germany, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
