<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / Spanish government believes peseta can ride out the storm
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TOM BURNS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MADRID
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE peseta yesterday traded just below its central parity in the European
exchange rate mechanism, reinforcing the Spanish government's belief that if
the ERM holds together the currency should be able to ride out the storm.
Mr Pedro Solbes, the economy and finance minister who took office last week
in a government reshuffle, said the peseta was resisting well the attacks on
the French franc and the Danish krone.
'I do not think that there are reasons for a fourth devaluation (of the
peseta),' Mr Solbes told El Pais yesterday.
The Bank of Spain took a similar bullish view at yesterday morning's
certificate repo tender. Confident that the peseta could defend itself
without recourse to interest rate rises, the central bank kept its key money
rate unchanged at 11 per cent.
By early afternoon the currency was trading at Pta80.20 against the D-Mark,
just over half a peseta down on the previous day's close. On Thursday the
peseta slid through its central parity of Pta79.11 against the D-Mark for
the first time since its 8 per cent devaluation on May 13 - its third
realignment within the ERM since September.
The peseta has a 6 per cent band within the ERM grid and it remains well off
its Pta84 floor.
'We're in the middle of the band. So what's the problem?' said Mr Jaime
Pinies, chief of research at Banco Santander de Negocios.
Analysts said that if the ERM overcame its present turmoil, there could be
renewed confidence in the peseta as the main features of Mr Solbes' economic
policy filtered through to the markets. In his interview the minister spoke
of budget austerity, case-by-case privatisations and a pact with unions to
cap salary increases.
'Speculators who are taking forward positions on the peseta are taking a big
risk,' said Mr Ignacio Montejo, chief economist at Madrid brokers FG.
Echoing a widely shared view that the currency's value was properly
corrected in the May devaluation, Mr Montejo said the peseta was 'cheap' as
soon as it fell below its central parity in the grid.
</TEXT>
