<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / Companies in south now entitled to aid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By OUR REGIONAL STAFF
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COMPANIES in parts of London and on the east and south coasts of England are
to be entitled for the first time to financial assistance from the
Department of Trade and Industry.
To qualify for the help they must invest to create new jobs or safeguard
existing ones.
The move follows a redrawing of the Assisted Areas map, which outlines areas
where regional aid subsidies may be paid. Mr Tim Sainsbury, the industry
minister, yesterday announced the areas covered by the first new map since
1984.
The old map concentrated assistance on industrial areas north of a line
drawn from The Wash to the River Severn. The new map brings in districts of
high unemployment in London such as Park Royal and the Lea Valley and
selected coastal areas running from Skegness, through Great Yarmouth, the
Isle of Thanet and Hastings to Torbay.
Areas hurt by coal mine closures, such as Chesterfield and Mansfield, or by
defence cuts, such as Barrow-in-Furness, have also been included.
To keep the proportion of the population covered by the map down to 34-35
per cent, parts of south and north Wales have been removed. So too have
parts of Manchester, Bradford and Midland towns such as Corby, Kidderminster
and Telford.
Regional aid payments are made under the terms of the Industrial Development
Act 1982. Areas entitled to aid are split into development or intermediate
areas, denoting the extent of subsidy which can be paid. Regional selective
assistance, which cost the government Pounds 193m in 1991-92, is used as a
carrot to attract inward investment.
The shape of the new map reflects the changing pattern of unemployment in
Britain. Areas of southern England, hurt by recession and the shakeout in
the service sector, have recorded unemployment figures higher than those
areas in the Midlands and north associated with industrial decline.
The government's choice of areas was predictably controversial. 'Extensions
to the map should not have been paid for by cuts elsewhere,' said Mr Robin
Cook, the shadow trade and industry secretary.
Mr Alan Milburn, the Labour MP for Darlington, which lost assisted status,
accused the government of gerrymandering the map 'to prop up crumbling Tory
support across the country'.
In Wales, Mr John Redwood, Welsh secretary, tried to steer criticism away by
saying that the majority of the working population continues to have
Assisted Area status but Mr Ron Davies, the shadow Welsh secretary, said
'the Welsh economy is too fragile to lose government aid of whatever type'.
