<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / France and Germany buy time in fight to boost franc
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEPHANIE FLANDERS and PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FRANCE and Germany yesterday bought time in their battle to keep the French
franc in the European exchange rate mechanism but there was no sign of an
early end to the crisis in Europe's currency markets.
Intervention, verbal support and an increase in the French central bank's
overnight lending rate to 10 per cent from 7.75 per cent were used to keep
the franc from falling to its FFr3.4305 floor against the D-Mark.
Other recently embattled ERM currencies saw a similar easing of pressure.
The Spanish peseta closed slightly up and the Portuguese escudo held its
own.
But although the French currency closed at FFr3.416, a little stronger than
Thursday's close of FFr3.419, dealers and currency market analysts predicted
that the tensions would reappear next week in the run-up to a meeting on
Thursday of the Bundesbank's decision-making central council.
In late trading in New York the franc fell back slightly to around
FFr3.4177.
In a rerun of moves earlier this year to deter speculation, the French and
German governments and the two countries' central banks 'reaffirmed' that
the parity between the D-Mark and the franc was 'fully in line with economic
fundamentals'.
They also sold D-Marks for francs in line with a pledge to 'continue to
co-operate' according to the rules of the ERM, although on a smaller scale
than Thursday.
Their message was reinforced by Mr Edouard Balladur, the French prime
minister, who said in Morocco that there would be no franc devaluation.
However, currency market operators reacted with scepticism and insisted that
there would be no peace in the system unless the Bundesbank cut its interest
rates by as much as 1 percentage point next week.
'I would judge that about 65 per cent to 70 per cent of our corporate
customers and investors think that the ERM is beyond the point of no
return,' said Mr Rob Loewy, head of currencies at Midland Global Markets in
London.
