<HEADLINE>
FT  24 JUL 93 / Major's victory fails to end leadership doubts: Confidence
motion carried by 40 votes - Euro-rebels fall in line but threaten revenge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR'S threat of a general election yesterday pulled the
Conservative party back from the brink of self-destruction as the House of
Commons finally gave its approval for ratification of the Maastricht treaty.
But the prime minister's easy victory in the confidence motion following
Thursday night's humiliating defeat over the treaty's social chapter failed
to remove the question mark over his premiership.
With Tory Eurosceptics threatening revenge after being forced to abandon
their rebellion and ministers acknowledging that Mr Major's authority had
suffered another blow, there was speculation about a leadership challenge in
the autumn.
Mr Major was joined by a phalanx of senior ministers in insisting that the
final parliamentary debate on the treaty  - only a legal challenge could
block ratification  - had drawn a line under the Tory civil war over Europe.
Mr Douglas Hurd, the foreign secretary, said the government was at a turning
point and predicted a decisive change in the political mood of the country
after 'the last speech in the last debate on the ratification of
Maastricht'. In public, both sides in the Conservative battle stressed their
determination to put behind them the bitterness of the past year. After
talks with the rebels, Mr Hurd acknowledged the strength of their conviction
that the treaty would erode Britain's sovereignty, while Sir Marcus Fox, the
chairman of the backbench 1922 Committee, said there would be no
'witch-hunt'.
The prime minister, speaking after the government had secured a majority of
40 in the crucial confidence vote in favour of ratification of Maastricht
with Britain's social chapter opt-out, denied that his position remained in
peril.
Stressing that the government would now move on to a domestic political
agenda designed to sustain the economic recovery and step up the fight
against crime, Mr Major said: 'I don't expect a leadership challenge in the
autumn.'
Echoing Mr Hurd's comments, Mr Major continued: 'I think the line has been
drawn today . . . as far as the Conservative party is concerned the matter
(Maastricht) is done and gone.'
But his optimism was not echoed among the ranks of ministers and
Conservative MPs packing the Commons chamber for the first confidence debate
called by a government in recent political history.
Mr Bill Cash, a leading Euro-sceptic, said in a TV interview: 'The whole
question is going to continue because now people are going to have to see if
the landscape that Maastricht does represent can actually work.'
Senior ministers said they expected a crushing defeat for the Tories at the
hands of Mr Paddy Ashdown's Liberal Democrats in next Thursday's by-election
in the once impregnable stronghold of Christchurch.
They conceded their hopes the government would regain its balance rested on
the respite offered by the long parliamentary recess which begins next
Tuesday. At least one cabinet minister was ready to predict 'a very rough
autumn' unless the economic recovery gathers further pace.
But Mr Major's tactics in threatening a general election if the Maastricht
treaty were not ratified successfully forced the Tory sceptics to abandon
the alliance with the opposition parties which triggered the government's
earlier defeat.
With their arguments against Maastricht dismissed by Mr Major as 'nonsense',
the 23 rebels who had voted against the government on Thursday all reversed
their allegiances.
With the government retaining the support of the Ulster unionists, a Labour
amendment to the confidence motion demanding that the government embrace the
treaty's social provision was defeated by 339 to 301 votes.
The motion of confidence was then won by the government by 339 to 299 votes.
Only one Conservative MP, Mr Rupert Allason, did not vote after failing to
return in time from abroad.
The confidence debate, while something of an anti-climax, underlined the
determination of Mr John Smith, Labour leader, to focus his party's attacks
on Mr Major's leadership.
In a savage assault, Mr Smith said the prime minister's 'authority and
credibility' had been destroyed by his handling of the Maastricht
legislation and by his refusal to embrace the treaty's social provisions.
